deck_excerpt: Updated version of Battlewasp Ballpark deck for Master Duel NR format.
deck_description: I have already participated in two Master Duel tournaments focused on the Normal/Rare Format. And I got addicted to building several decks of this format because it's an event still little explored and full of good archetype ideas to use. The deck I present below is the improved version of the first Master Duel Normal/Rare deck I built: https://ygoprodeck.com/battlewasp-ballpark-nr-event-mar22/ Lately I stopped playing Master Duel because I have an error problem that prevents me from playing any game because a window appears that closes the game. I've already talked to the game's support and they gave me a lot of attention but the fact is that even with a print screen and details of how the error happens, I haven't been able to play for almost a month. So I decided to make some deck profiles of decks I had built in Normal/Rare Format and share my latest content related to Master Duel. //////////////////////////////////////////////// /// As I had already explained in the other deck profile the idea behind the deck and the synergies between the main cards used, here I will focus on the interactions I noticed when using the deck in tournaments that allowed me to improve it a lot. Shinobi and Gokipole Interaction: You make the Shinobi Insect Hagakuremino using the Gokipole as a material and pointing at an opponent's monster and the Gokipole uses its Special Summon effect from Vanilla Shiny Black "C" Squadder in the zone the Shinobi points to and destroys the opponent's monster that Shinobi points to which triggers the Shinobi's eff to give Reborn from Sting the Poison for example and you do Synchro-6 Battlewasp - Halberd the Charge to end the game. In other situations you can Reborn a Level 3 Insect to make XYZ Summon rolls. I've won several games just because of this interaction. Just remember that when making Shinobi using Gokipole and Battlewasp - Twinbow the Attacker you don't first bring Gokipole with Shinobi after the opponent's monster is destroyed, but Twinbow because he will be banished when he leaves the field and will not use its search effect. This same interaction is valid for Puzzlomino and Gokipole: You make Puzzlomino, the Drop-n-Deleter using Gokipole as material and bring Vanilla Shiny Black "C" Squadder in the zone he points and destroy an opponent's monster and you will still be able to manipulate its level to destroy another opponent's monster or make XYZ Summon or Synchro Summon plays. So Puzzlomino is another interaction and versatility card available in the Extra Deck when you are not locked in Insects. //////////////////////////////////////////////// /// Technoplay and Missplays I made with the deck: You should think a lot about the best time to use Reborn spell Revival Swarm eff in GY to protect one of your Insect monsters from destruction. For example I already lost a game because I decided not to protect Synchro-6 Battlewasp - Halberd the Charge with it since I had Torrential Tribute set to use on the opponent's turn. Another mistake I made a few times was when using the Giant Ballpark effect to send to the GY because the decision to special summon 1, 2 or 3 copies of Shiny Black "C" Squadder is important for example if you drop 1 Vanilla in the Main Deck on your next turn you will be able to use this special summon effect again, which in this case would be the 3 Vanillas. So don't bring the 3 Shiny Black "C" Squadder Vanillas straight onto the field the first time you activate the Giant Ballpark effect. There's also the interaction between Special Summoning 2 Lv4 Vanilla and you do RANK-4 Insect Number 70: Malevolent Sin and then RANK-5 Digital Bug Corebage on top to have interaction of returning a defense position monster to the deck . Another missplay that you shouldn't commit when using Giant Ballpark is that its floating effect of giving Vanilla Reborn is only when an Insect is destroyed by an opponent's card effect. So first that if you destroy your monsters with Torrential Tribute, Ballpark won't trigger eff from Reborn to Vanilla, and second that it won't trigger eff if the monsters are destroyed in battle so think carefully about using this card so you don't missplay in battle phase for example thinking she would give Vanilla Reborn. MISSPLAY: You have a lot of cards that need to discard as cost to work so don't keep setting cards on the field for no reason as when you need a discard in your hand to resolve a Dinomischus or Lightning Vortex this mistake will cost you the game. MISSPLAY: You don't summon Synchro 6 Battlewasp - Halberd the Charge in the Extra Monster Zone Column to make the Shinobi Co-Linked so the opponent can target him for attacks. //////////////////////////////////////////////// /// In a format like this N/R with slower games and Spell/Traps based interactions you should save your Backrow removal as a Mystical Space Typhoon to use on the right cards. It's not to use Mystical Space Typhoon blindly, for example, but to wait for the game to develop a little to destroy the correct backrow. //////////////////////////////////////////////// // Disregard the Side Deck, they are just examples of interesting cards to test in the deck.

deck_excerpt: Phantasm Spiral for Master Duel Normal/Rare format
deck_description: Phantasm Spiral is an Anti-Meta style deck that works around Normal Monsters, with the deck's Boss Monster being the Phantasm Spiral Dragon. But the archetype's main card is the excellent Field Spell Pacifis, the Phantasm City that you want access to as soon as possible. In the N/R format version many consistency cards don't exist so we have to adapt the deck with the best in the format like Link Apple which is basically an Upstart Goblin "free to play" and Planet Pathfinder which is 3 more copies from Pacifis, the Phantasm City. (One detail about how Phantasm Spiral cards work is that monsters from the Extra Deck with No effect are not considered Normal monsters like Monk of the Tenyi or Gem-Knight Pearl which is used in the Extra Deck just for decoration because it's correct you never do them as this disables their interaction traps like Phantasm Spiral Battle and Phantasm Spiral Power) /////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////Comments on cards and deck gameplay: One of the biggest problems with this Archetype is that you have practically no interaction with the opponent until you control a Normal Monster since almost all spell/traps need this condition in order to activate their effects. And there's the fact that if your opponent is smart he can easily play around Pacifis, the Phantasm City by not activating any card effects but trying to win on the basis of Beatdown by putting monsters on the field and going straight to the Battle Phase. That's why I decided to give up using Megalosmasher X which has the synergy of being a WATER monster with the Trap Sea Stealth Attack that can banish it to protect Pacifis, the Phantasm City from being destroyed to use the Mekk-Knight engine: World Legacy's Memory and Mekk-Knight Avram, these two cards play the role of Unexpected Dai better since you can use it on your opponent's turn and the monster Special Summoned by World Legacy's Memory will be returned to the hand in the End Phase which means you can Normal Summon Mekk-Knight Avram on your next turn and trigger the effect of Pacifis, the Phantasm City to add another Archetype card and build pressure on the opponent faster than compared to Unexpected Dai and Megalosmasher X . The only thing about using World Legacy's Memory is that it conflicts with Pacifis, the Phantasm City effect of creating Token so it has to be used after creating the Token to Summon Mekk-Knight Avram. Other synergies of this engine: World Legacy's Memory makes Planet Pathfinder even better in the deck because before you had to choose between Normal Summoning Megalosmasher X or Pathfinder but now you have the option to bring Vanilla straight from the deck. And about Mekk-Knight Avram coming back into the hand in the End Phase you get a simple discard way to use Paleozoic Dinomischus. So the improvements in using this engine are better than any other option available in Normal/Rare format. Basically Phantasm Spiral Battle allows you to catch the opponent off guard when for example you used the effect of one of the Equip and it is now equipped on the Boss Monster of the deck and now it's the opponent's turn and he declares an attack on your monster that doesn't have the equip spell, you can activate Trap Phantasm Spiral Battle in the attack declaration and return the Equip Spell to your monster that is participating in the battle and take advantage of that battle phase in the opponent's turn. The best Equip spell is Phantasm Spiral WAVE because your monster doesn't need to have battled an opponent's monster to resolve and bring the boss monster, as well as forcing the opponent to discard a card from their hand. Sea Stealth Attack is the best way to get rid of the token on the field so you can use the field's effect again to generate advantage and interaction every turn. Mainly do this on your turn to enter the Opponent's Turn without Token if Already have another Normal Monster on the Field. Another Missplay with Sea Stealth Attack is not banishing NORMAL Monsters knowing that you will need to use TORRENTIAL TRIBUTE. (Know that using Sea Stealth Attack eff on Megalosmasher X per example will count as a monster that returns to the field in the End Phase and not a Special Summon so you will never get trigger eff from FIELD Pacifis, the Phantasm City with this effect) The Field spell Pacifis, the Phantasm City basically works like this: The Phantasm Spiral Token create effect is not once per turn and the add effect from deck to hand is MANDATORY. The Tenyi Counter Trap Fists of the Unrivaled Tenyi only negates spell/trap activation and not their effect on the GY like Eldlich's traps like Conquistador of the Golden Land and True Draco cards like True Draco Heritage. Don't forget how important Paleozoic Traps are in the deck coming back from the GY as a Normal Monster having a lot of synergy with deck cards that get dead while a normal monster is not on the field. Interaction between Sea Stealth and Paleozoic Traps: you can activate Sea Stealth Attack and in chain activate the Paleozoic Traps in GY to gain access to a Normal Monster. //////////////////////////////////////////////// ////////////Deck issues: Lack of pressure and consistency due to reliance on Field Spell Pacifis, the Phantasm City alongside cards like Sea Stealth Attack to capitalize on advantage. So in addition to having a certain dependence on the opponent's actions, what you do is never enough to control the game, you are always losing until the moment when the opponent's pushes miraculously end and you win. That's why this is a deck that won't tolerate Missplay on your part. //////////////////////////////////////////////// //////////// Disregard the Side Deck, they are just card options to test in the Main Deck.

deck_excerpt: This is one of the most unknown decks in the NR format
deck_description: Nephthys is a deck that emerged from a proposal that exists in a few archetypes in the game, which is to take a very old card from the game as a base and make an entire deck to support this monster. Here this monster is the Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys which is so old that I remember using this card over 12 years ago. Other decks that work with this theme are: Dinosaur structure deck that plays around the Babycerasaurus card and the Thunder Dragon deck that was made to support the iconic early game card. The Nephthys deck works on the basis of Ritual Summon mechanics and has good Ritual monsters which already makes it a decent deck since when it comes to Ritual Summon if the deck cannot generate an advantage while Ritual Summoning it practically becomes unplayable but this is not the case with Nephthys. This archetype preserves some characteristics found on the Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys card mainly the fact that they work by destroying your cards to use their effects and also have effects when they are destroyed. The biggest problem with the Nephthys deck is that they copied the Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys part of activating their effects on the GY only on their next Standby Phase which makes them slow cards for Yugioh! Modern. However, we are talking about the use of this deck in NR format and here the Nephthys deck is not that slow, even having a competitive attachment. /////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////Nephthys Gameplay Details: The main idea of ​​the deck is to make the following combo: - Use Manju or Disciple of Nephthys eff to add the missing combo piece to the hand either Devotee of Nephthys which can be added with both cards or Ritual Spell Rebirth of Nephthys which can be added by Manju. - Having the Ritual spell and monster you Ritual Summon Devotee of Nephthys. Then use Devotee eff and special Disciple of Nephthys straight from the deck. (If you already control Disciple and used effect on turn you can bring it to Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys or Matriarch of Nephthys from Deck) - Disciple is the ROTA of both Monster and Spell/Trap. In this case the monster you add is the Matriarch of Nephthys (Follow Up) but it depends on the rest of your hand. - Use Disciple and Devotee to LINK-2 Nephthys, the Sacred Preserver and eff to Add Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys (single target possible) from Deck and Ritual Spell Rebirth of Nephthys from GY. - Using Devotee of Nephthys eff destroys Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys in Hand to Special itself and the Sacred Phoenix already comes into circulation on returning from GY in the Standby Phase of your next turn destroying all the backrow on the field. If you use Devotee of Nephthys itself to Ritual Summon Devotee you get an additional pop from the Ritual Spell Rebirth of Nephthys so always try to capitalize on that play by Ritual Summoning and surprising your opponent by destroying their cards without targeting. One way to take advantage of Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys is with SPELL Last Hope of Nephthys destroying it and an opponent's card. If you have 2 Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys in the GY that were destroyed and you are in your Standby Phase, what happens will be that both of them return to the field with their mandatory effects and activate their mandatory effect to destroy the spells/traps on the field as well. In this NR format build, arriving at the Devotee of Nephthys Ritual Summon is the main move to be made, so even if you don't come with your hand aligned, always seek to access the missing pieces like Devotee and the Ritual Spell Rebirth of Nephthys as soon. Cool that you destroying the Paleozoic Traps in your HAND to use the Disciple of Nephthys effect per example doesn't generate you any downside because they come back from the GY allowing RANK-2 plays. Matriarch of Nephthys allows accessing RANK-2 moves very easily so it is common in the grind game to use Disciple of Nephthys to add Matriarch to be your Normal Summon. And you can use Disciple to destroy the Matriarch if you have it in hand and the Matriarch goes back to the field in the next Standby Phase and gives Disciple Reborn if it's in the GY. The LINK-2 Nephthys, the Sacred Preserver is like a Preparation of Rites in the sense that it can give you a Plus 1 if you have a Ritual Spell in your GY which most of the time you do it you will. And his effect of destroying a "Nephthys" and bringing a different name instead is very useful to Loop the Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys during SP to clear Backrow. Torrential Tribute triggers eff from your Nephthys monsters so losing your board is no problem because your cards have floating effects in the Standby Phase. Interaction with Geonator Transverser is also very cool because if you gave SS from Matriarch of Nephthys in the Standby Phase by its own effect and gave Reborn from Devotee of Nephthys from GY and made Geonator Transverser you can use Devotee eff in GY to get back on Geonator's arrow and that way you can exchange the control of monsters. ///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////// Disregard the Side Deck, they are just examples of cards to test in the deck.

Eldlich has been a very viable, and despised, meta-archetype since its release, often a backrow heavy deck that abuses floodgates, however more combo-oriented variants of the deck have been popping up, such as Cyberse, Branded, and Invoked. These decks exchange the excessive use of floodgates and backrow for use of combo starters such as Halqifibrax, Aluber, and Aleister, they are much more fun to play than their base version and make good use of Eldlich's recursive potential for maintain advantage.  For the decklist, we have an Eldlich package of 3x Eldlich, 2x Eldland, 3x Conquistador, 3x Huaquero, and 3x Scarlet Sanguine, a Cyberse package, 3x Gadget, 3x Firewall Guardian, 2x Dotscaper, 1x Accesscode, 1x Transcode, 1x Splash Mage, 1x Devotee, 1x Disciple, 1x Linguriboh, and 1x Linkuriboh, for the rest of the Main Deck, we have my preferred Handtrap lineup of 2x Nibiru, 3x Ash Blossom, 2x Ghost Belle, and 2x Veiler, 1x Scythe, 1x Lancea, 1x Jet Synchron, 1x Change of Heart, 1x One for One, 1x Avarice, 1x Called By, 2x Twin Twisters, 1x Underworld Goddess, 1x Trisbaena, 1x Knightmare Unicorn, 2x Dagda, 1x Link Spider, 1x Imduk, and 1x Anima.

I'm not great with VW, but I understand their bread and butters, and I know it can end on VFD. PUNK also ends on VFD off of 1 card. So, we're trying to cheese free games.  Still tuning this one (and TBH, learning VW lines). The deck is very good at making VFD, but struggles to back it with much out - either they can out it or they can't. Still, I decided to add a second Shenshen to the mix, so that you can use 1 with Dragon Mech for VFD and then put up Crocodragon and Shenshen alongside it.  This deck is pretty crazy - it makes VFD pretty easily, often through interruption, and Omega and Baroness (I respect milady's gender, unlike Konami!) also come up a lot more often than I thought they would. This list is pretty crazy in testing so far - VFD + Shenshen, + traps and sometimes another 8-10 synchro (Omega, Crocofish, or Baroness)  Still tuning the deck. Finding space for hand traps is tight in this format - you really want Gamma and Ghost Ogre, just for the E-Tele package, even though the format is a Maxx "C" format, and you just don't have the space for it IMO. Qinglong isn't great to see, but it will start VW plays with another VW, such a Lulu, so I wanted 3, but I also really wanted Foolish Burial Goods to be a Monster Reborn / ROTA for the deck (a little worse than that, since your gates do get used in combos, but it will enable plays). Ultimately, I cut it to 2 Qinglong to make space for the hand traps. PUNK engine is on 9 starters, down from 10 - this is a bit high, but it also means you can bait interruptions pretty well, and have great odds of starting with PUNK plays. 10 was a little too bricky, but I like the idea of using Ogre Dance for more consistency, even as a 1 of. I like 2 Chuche, I don't hate seeing the card, but it can be easily sent from the deck for its GY effect, it is better activated with the spell card than set in your combos, and it just doesn't do a lot in your combos. I'm considering Pot of Avarice - the deck already has a couple of ways to loop banished cards back into the deck, and this could rebuild your combos to pull it off again in a grind game, or even just make the Crocodragon a disruption instead of just an empty threat.  The hand trap line-up is pretty simple. I'm on 2 Ghost Ogre - running this makes E-Tele a disruptive card if it resolves, which is tight, and it helps that it is an emergency level 3 tuner. We've also got a suite out of respect to Maxx "C" - this is a combo deck that puts up a lot of bodies, so we need an insect answer. Called By is potentially a bannable card, and we're running both allowed copies. Ash is nice and generic, I think it is almost mandatory in a Maxx "C" format, but I'm on 2, because Gamma can also answer the insect while being higher quality as a disruption and defensive card. Gamma is the more important E-Tele target between it and Ghost Ogre - usually you'll be summoning a PUNK or VW card, but if not Gamma is enabling an Omega or Baroness. Lastly, there was space for a lone Maxx "C" - on the one hand, this is a super sacky 1 of, but on the other, with 2 ofs your other hand traps and no redundant copies, you won't have the problem of drawing Maxx "C" or other redundant interruptions as much as in a deck spamming 3 copies of its cards.  Cut Ghost Ogre - might be a good card in the shell once Brave hits the format, but in the meantime, there are too many other high quality targets for E-Tele to ever need to summon Ogre, and I needed space for the essentials. I'm still shy 1 Maxx "C" but there just isn't the space.  I'm testing a larger version of the deck - in theory, this should allow me to get better ratios on my hand traps, as well as giving me the space to run more tech cards. I'm at 55 cards, which means my PUNK package is about 1/5 of the deck (good odds for a 1/5 hand, no?). The VW part gets slightly sketchier, in theory, but in reality it seems absolutely fine. I decided that 55 cards with 3 Avarice would give me excellent ratios on my hand traps and VW starting combos, while also giving me a little bit of gas, and the ability to rebuild my extra deck in a grind game. I'm not sure Avarice will make the cut in the long run, it is kinda sketchy and a little bit "win more", but this deck could also genuinely use it after it has burnt up its combo to try again, and fills the GY very easily with either the PUNK or the VW engines. I cut Zeus, because it was barely coming up, and replace with with the PUNK Dragon, which will also probably barely come up, but hey, it's a really removal effect on the card, and the recovery is also nice, and besides, if I'm playing PUNK cards might as well make the new best 11 synch in the game.  Back to a nice, tight, 40 card list. The other list was consistent enough, but if the PUNK engine got stopped before Crocodragon it didn't consistently have Virtual World plays, which is sad, so instead we're running a much tighter list, with a single Ghost Ogre - you shouldn't usually need it off of E-Tele, but you often have it when you do.

deck_excerpt: Branded and Dual Avatar locks you into fusion summon only, Dual Avatar and Generaider both generate a lot of tokens and both have a field spell. I hav
deck_description:
Just some pile of cards i put together, there are no actual synergies except Branded and Dual Avatar locks your extra deck into fusion only, and Generaider and Dual Avatar both generate tokens You could maybe put in Loptr for the normal summon to summon Mardel to search the Boss Stage, but usually Yuhi eat the normal summon more often when you didn't open Invitation or Fusion Deployment I didn't run any Dual Avatar trap even tho Kokoku could search it, i just feel like they're just not that good. You could run Dual Avatar Ascendance maybe just for a discard cost since it has a graveyard effect You could change Fists of the Unrivaled Tenyi for any other handtraps (And yeah the Blue-Eyes Ultimate Dragon is there for its target) You could also add ROTA if you want, i just dunno what to change and i wanna keep the deck 40 And since Verte is banned, you have to hard draw the Branded Fusion

The Deck......Breakdown....?:

  • Branded Fusion alone is an interruption on it's own, 1 card = Mirrorjade, non target monster banish
  • Boss Stage or Boss Fight is also an interruption on it's own, just activate it, wait for your opponent's turn and pray they didn't have Ghost Ogre or any quickplay backrow hate (or Token Collector), summon Harr for omni negate, Utgarda for another quick banish, or Hela if you have Harr/Utgarda in your gy
  • Perfect Sync - A-Un could search Yuhi, normal summon it, use the field effect to summon a token, then use Yuhi effect to destroy the token to search Invitation, or if you don't open the field spell, Yuhi could destroy itself. If you already open Yuhi and Invitation you could search for Kokoku instead
  • If you're going first you would want to summon Mitsu-Jaku (for battle protection and quick destroy a monster that activates its effect) and Un-Gyo (For bad effect destruction protection and extra deck monster negation)
  • If you're going second you would want to summon Kon-Gyo (it could bounce a monster after damage calc and it has a target protection) and Ah-Gyo (to destroy atk position monster but it cannot atk this turn, and it could boost atk)
Well this is just a fun casual non meta deck so don't expect this to be any good lol

Use Halq to summon Scopen from the deck (treated as level 4 in def) and tune it with a Celfon for Hyper Librarian. Now each time you summon a Formula Synchron using a Celfon and a Smartfon/Telefon you'll draw 2 cards. A Smartfon in def lets you stack your deck as well, so you'll get to draw the cards you actually want (useful when you only have tuners on the field to ensure you can add a spell with Princessprite). When your field is full, link everything (besides Librarian) away for Saryuja to get 4 more draws (the special summon from hand is helpful too). Repeat using Telefon targeting another copy of itself/Junk Box and Pot of Avarice (shuffle Extra Deck monsters or Celfons to potentially make another copy of Machine Dupe live again) till you get all pieces. Consistent enough to get a decent hand and can play through some handtraps with Junk Box, since the -fons are all sopt's and Telefon can get enough Link fodder on the field with a good grave. You can also switch the one-of draw spells and Where arf thou? with a Crossout package to be better off against handtraps.

deck_description: If you open ok (which imo is pretty consistent) you will end on charles, baronne, stellar wind wolfrayet, and halq + chaos ruler + a token which will tag out for trish zero, banishing 3 The Combo: Starting with isolde (which adds gearfried) plus a tuner (specifically arboria or oliver, making sure you dont use durendal): 1- Activate isolde, sending phoenix blade and fleuret de fleur to summon doppelwarrior 2- Summon halq with the tuner and isolde, summoning jet synchron 3- Summon martial metal marcher, activating its trigger effect to revive jet along with the 2 tokens 4- Summon celestial double star shaman with jet and a token, reviving doppel 5- Summon cupid pitch with the double star and doppel, using its effect to increase its level 6- Summon power tool with cupid pitch and a token, using cupid pitch to grab catche eve l2 and power tool to grab durendal 7- Summon garden rose maiden, grabbing black garden 8- Activate catche eve l2 to reduce the level of the rose maiden and summon it 9- Activate black garden and then summon roland with the rose maiden and catche eve l2, summoning a token to the opposite field 10- Activate black gardens effect to pop itself and the token to revive doppelwarrior, then use durendal to get renaud 11- Special renaud as a tuner and use its effect to add fleuret de fleur back to your hand 12- Summon the 2nd power tool with roland and the doppelwarrior, adding ddr 13- Summon stellar wind wolfrayet with one power tool, renaud, and a token 14- Activate phoenix blade, banishing whatever doesnt matter, then use jet synchron to discard it and summon itself 15- Summon chaos ruler with the other power tool and jet, you can activate its effect if you want but it kinda does nothing 16- Activate phoenix blade banishing some used up stuff again, then discard it with ddr to bring back the jet synchron again 17- Summon charles with the chaos ruler and the jet synchron 18- Activate rose maiden in grave to revive the chaos ruler 19- Activate fleuret de fleur on the double star shaman, then summon baronne with it and the chaos ruler 20- Activate chaos ruler's effect in grave to summon it 21- In end step activate charles, equipping phoenix blade from grave to equip ogier or oliver from deck, then pop the phoenix blade, and then add the therion with roland 22- your opponent ash/veiler/impermed your isolde, or activated nib before your halq even came out, so none of that happened anyway

Earth Machine, also known as Machina Infinitrack, is a group of primarily Earth-Attribute, Machine-Type monsters that synergize very well with each other, and as several Infintrack monsters are Level 5, also allows you to go to into Cyber Dragon Nova, as well as Infinity. Infinitrack Tunneller is an excellent resource for the deck, essentially being a Pot of Avarice, and can be returned with Machina Overdrive, basically a mini Pot of Avarice, making a very good resource loop that allows for some longevity in drawn out games.  For the decklist, we have a Machina package of 1x Citadel, 1x Metalcruncher,  1x Fortress, 3x Gearframe, 2x Redeployment, and 3x Overdrive, an Infinitrack package of 1x Tunneller, 2x Brutal Dozer, 2x Trencher, 2x Anchor Drill, 3x Harvester, 2x Heavy Forward, 1x River Stormer, 1x Megaclops, and 3x Goliath, for the rest of the Main Deck, we have my preferred Handtrap lineup of 3x Ash Blossom, 2x Ghost Belle, and 2x Veiler, 1x Avarice, 1x Called By, 2x Droplet, 3x Urgent Schedule, and 3x Crossout Designator, for the rest of the Extra Deck, we have 1x Zeus, 1x Liebe, 1x Super Dora, 1x Gustav Max, 2x Cyber Dragon Infinity, 3x Cyber Dragon Nova, and 1x Underworld Goddess.

Drytron, the much hated, former meta dominating archetype is a very powerful series of cards that make use of actually insane busted cards, that make use of one of the worst mechanics in Yu-Gi-Oh, Ritual Summoning. In the past, Ritual based archetypes have gotten some very powerful cards, but have almost always failed to make the mechanic viable. Especially, now that Drytron has access to 2x Benten, even though they don't have Eva anymore, Drytron can still a force to be reckoned with, until they get Dark Ruler'd in Game 2. : )  For the decklist, we have a Drytron Package of 3x Alpha, 2x Delta, 2x Gamma, 3x Zeta, 1x Draconids, 1x Quadrantids, 1x Fafnir, 3x Cyber Emergency, 3x Nova, 2x Meteonis, and 2x Mu Beta, a Ritual package of 3x Diviner, 1x Ultimateness, 2x Benten, 2x Preparation of Rites, and 3x Arc Light, for the rest of the Main Deck, we have my preferred Handtrap lineup of 3x Ah Blossom, 2x Ghost Belle, 3x Orange Light, and 2x Veiler, 1x Called By, for the rest of the Extra Deck, we have 1x Zeus, 1x Beatrice, 1x Downerd, 1x Assembled Nightingale, 1x Underworld Goddess, 1x Accesscode, 1x Knightmare Unicorn, 1x Masquerena, 1x Linkuriboh, 1x Relinquished Anima

Endymion is an archetype of Pendulum monsters that make use of Spell Counters, these cards gain Spell Counters when Spell cards are activated, which includes putting a card in the Pendulum Zones. While it is banned in the TCG, Heavymetalfoes Electrumite is legal in the OCG, and is a great asset to any Pendulum deck, allowing for a lot of shenanigans with cards like Astrograph Sorcerer.  For the decklist, we have an Endymion package of 3x Mighty Master, 2x Empress, 2x Magister, 2x Servant, 3x Spell Power, 1x Magical Citadel(and 1x Terraforming for it), and 3x Selene, for the rest of the Main Deck, we have my preferred Handtraps lineup of 3x Ash Blossom, 2x Ghost Belle, 3x Maxx C, and 2x Veiler, 1x Mythical Beast Master Cerberus, 1x Astrograph Sorcerer, 1x Mythical Beast Jackal King, 1x Mythical Beast Garuda, 2x Desires(if it was at 3 we would play 3x), 1x Avarice, 3x Upstart Goblin, 2x Called By, and 3x Chicken Game, for the rest of the Extra Deck, we have 2x Supreme King Dragon Starving Venom, 2x Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon, 2x Odd-Eyes Absolute Dragon, 1x Underworld Goddess, 1x Accesscode, 1x Halqifibrax, 1x Cross-Sheep, and 1x Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden.

Gravekeepers is a fan favourite archetype from DM that has gotten a lot of Legacy support that revolves around the Field Spell Necrovalley and countering GY effects. They have cards like Commandant, which searches for Necrovalley(basically giving you 4x Terraforming), and Heretic, which is unaffected by all other card effects(which includes the ATK Boost from Necrovalley). This archetype doesn't really use the Extra Deck either, allowing them to work very well with the Dogmatika archetype, which prevent you summoning from your Extra Deck, as well as counter your Opponent's monsters summoned from the Extra Deck.  For the decklist, we have a Gravekeeper package of 2x Heretic, 3x Commandant, 2x Spiritualist, 2x Necrovalley Throne, 2x Royal Tribute, 2x Hidden Temples of Necrovalley, 3x Necrovalley(and 1x Terraforming for it), and 2x Supernaturalist, we have a Dogmatika package of 1x Fleurdelis, 2x Maximus, 3x Ecclesia, 2x Nadir Servant(if it were at 3 we would be running 3x), 2x Punishment, and 2x Titaniklad, for the rest of the Main Deck, we have my preferred Handtrap lineup of 3x Ash Blossom, 2x Ghost Belle, and 2x Veiler, 3x Duality, 1x Called By, and 2x Solemn Judgement, for the rest of the Extra Deck, we have 2x Five-Headed Dragon, 2x Fossil Warrior Skull Knight, 2x Fossil Machine Skull Wagon, 2x N'tss, 1x PSY-Framelord Omega, 1x Wind Pegasus @Ignister, and 1x Underworld Goddess(just a lot of Extra Deck monsters with GY effects)

deck_excerpt: This deck is simply a Swordsoul Synchro deck but it can do the scythe lock with Dagda, Halqifibrax and Wonder Magician. Ratios may be improved by remo
deck_description: This deck contains the Brave engine, the Swordsouls engine, the Tenyi engine and finaly, you can scythe lock your opponent using Halqifibrax, Dagda and Wonder Magician.

Swordsoul is a Synchro based Wyrm-Type archetype, basically more generic Wyrm synchros. It is capable of breaking boards quite easily in-engine going second, but is also able to put up incredible interruptions going first, and has decent grind game. I'd call it a combo deck, but a very midrangey combo deck, and I like to play towards that grind game. This list incorporates a small PUNK package, DPE, Halq+Auroradon shenanigans, and a pile of Wyrm and goodstuff synchro monsters.  So, for Punk monsters, I'm on a package of 7 cards. The idea behind this package is pretty simple - it enables Halq-Auroradon starts, or Verte follow-ups. The way it works is you NS Ze Amin, search Foxy Tune, discard Foxy Tune and pitch a card to special Madame Spider. Madame Spider searches the Trap, which is basically Imperm for most intents and purposes, then you go into Halq. The combo has 2 main routes - you either Summon Yazi and pop him to summon out a Swordsoul level 4, usually with the intention of making 2 8s or an 8 and a 10, or you make Baroness right away with Deskbot and the tokens, and then NS a Swordsoul monster to continue your combo from there. The real appeal to this package is Emergency Teleport - this allows you to make Halq (or occasionally Verte) without using your NS, and while it does require pitching a card, it replaces it with an interruption. 2 E-Tele is mandatory if you run this package - this is the best PUNK card. 2 Ze Amin are run just because of E-Tele - When you see E-Tele + Ze Amin you can summon another from your deck and pitch the one in your hand for free consistency and starts without a normal. Otherwise you'd run 2 Foxy Tune, which does still require your NS to do full combo, but also works as a sort of extender when you see your PUNK cards. The Spider and Dangerous Gabu are optional - you could run a third Ze Amin for more consistent starts, or you could replace the "bricks" in the main deck with 1 in the extra deck with the Fusion monster and run the Sharakusai instead of Spider, which will help you start more often. I don't have space in this version for Sharakusai in the extra deck, and I don't think Spider, a card that just plusses you by finding an interruption is that hard a brick - the trap with no real activation requirement beyond a monster being on your opponent's field is definitely not. This option mitigates the cost of discarding a card, and even helps you with consistency. Just don't be afraid to pitch the Spider instead of Normal Summoning it if that will make your end board bigger - the goal isn't to always search Gabu, Gabu is a nice bonus you'll find more often than not. However, if you don't like DPE you could consider Ogre Dance or Sharakusai in the package.  DPE bricks are here. You'll see Fusion Destiny often enough, and this whole package all together is insane, much more than the sum of its parts. DPE here can trigger Chengying, help recurr Ecclesia, the Draw 2 is actually very much appreciated. It also just does usual DPE things, being a good backup plan. I should note that you won't be adding DPE to your boards very often, and should consider the setups for it that you have available. For example, Chixiao could link with a Tenyi monster (not the link) into Verte, and while you'd just be "exchanging" an interruption, having the Draw 2 on the table is really sweet. Likewise, Omega is potentially great material for DPE. Interestingly, you can happily pitch a Destiny HERO monster to the PUNK engine in this deck, and just recover the HERO with Omega later, especially since you aren't reliant on DPE. Having said that, this is IMO the perfect DPE shell (at least, while Verte is legal - after that probably just Fusion decks I think).  I'm on Tenyis. 2 Adhara, 2 Vishuda. Used together, they can make Halq and go into the Auroradon lines. If you SS Vishuda and NS Adhara you can immediately make a Baxia to spin 2 cards. Also, both of the GY effects are super relevant. I'm keeping these packages small: Vishuda is great going second as a board breaking tool and Adhara enables combos and seriously helps with the grind, and they actually also enable Halq, DPE, and Baxia, so these are good. Nonetheless, I don't want too many Tenyi monsters clogging my hand.  1 Deskbot, because it SS itself from the GY for Auroradon lines. If you're looking for a bigger combo, a single O-Lion or Coltwing would enable a lot without changing the list very much - if you work at it, big Denglong combos are possible, but IMO they involve too many bricks and are just "win more". Either they stopped you before that, they have Droplets, or you're probably winning anyway. You could also run a single Jet Synchron with a link monster to go into, which would allow you to do Auroradon combos using either Jet or Deskbot to make Halq, and Jet will be a 1 card Halq (more interesting if you aren't already on 3/4 PUNK NS).  Swordsoul Emergence looks like just another ROTA, but oddly enough it is one of the deck's main 1 card starters, and by itself it can make an 8, or a Yazi going second. Also, strangely, the usual benefits of running Rotas to pull combos together aren't really here, or at least not to the same degree. Still, this card is very good, and I'm glad I found space for all 3. Sacred Summit is fine as a 1 of - sometimes it can revive a Swordsoul Synchro monster, sometimes even turn 1 after linking it off, but its main purpose is activating both Swordsoul level 4 effects in the same turn, and it is important to your main combo lines. Taia is fine as a 1 of - you search it out or summon it from the deck, but don't want to see it very much otherwise, and you can recycle 1 copy because Omega should be banned. I'm on 2 of the rest - Ecclesia basically stands in for either level 4 Swordsoul, and can SS itself going second, and recycles itself off of DPE doing DPE things, Mo-Ye is just better Taia a lot of the time, making easy 8s and drawing a card (in a way that chain blocks the 8). We're only on 2 Mo-Ye because you need 2 copies in rotation for follow-ups to be smooth, you kinda don't want to see it that much - however, it is fine to NS, and just play Swordsoul like Konami and God intended. We're on 2 Longyuan because I think you do want to see this card a fair bit, this is the easy 10 added to a lot of boards, sometimes it helps make Baroness before you start your combo which is impressive, the burn is medium but has actually mattered in a fair few matches, and while you want to search it out you would rather search out Sacred Summit or the Blackout if you could.  So, Ash, Maxx "C", and Called By the Grave are pretty standard, but we're not on a lot of hand traps after that. Why? Well, Swordsoul abilities are great at breaking boards, and cards like Fusion Destiny really help create pressure as well. Vishuda also ends up being Imperm or better in a lot of situations (often much better). The lone Ghost Ogre makes the cut because we're low on E-Tele targets, and also this way E-Tele represents an interruption at best, and an information hazard at worst (when often, drawn late into the combo, it would be dead otherwise). If Vishuda is one half of Imperm, Gabu is the other half - it is here because it is searchable, nobody is running this over Lost Wind, let alone Imperm, but the card is good. We're on 2 Blackout - I really like this card, but here it is also our only backrow hate. I like relying on traps to answer backrow anyways - gets around IO and Secret Village. I feel like Solemn Judgment is really good here - you're often trying to create scenarios where you can protect Chengying in multiple ways while having a way or two to trigger him. Solemn is just a good solid negation effect that handles a lot of the board breaking cards that can help against us (including most hands with Droplets against generic decks).  So, Extra deck, real quick -  1 Monk of the Tenyi. I'd love a second of these, don't burn your Monk up if you don't have to. Remember you can turn your Tenyi's on with Swordsoul tokens, and only make Monk when you have to. Still, space is too tight for 2, and you absolutely need 1.  1 Verte with 1 DPE. You won't make Verte a lot, you're usually hard drawing the Fusion Destiny, but you'll get stopped and make DPE on occasion, and you should run it while it is legal. It also opens up new routes to different high-end boards (if you use your thinker).  1 Needlefibre, 1 Auroradon. These 2, always causing trouble. This combo is stupid, and tuner + any other monster is 5 zones filled and another effect on top of it? I still say Halq needs to be banned - Auroradon might be a problem without it, but I'd be inclined to let it operate alone, because whenever this card is a problem it is with Halq.  Yazi is insane going second, and part of the main Halq line, so this one is mandatory. It is easier to make than you'd think.  2 Baxia. This card is good removal, another tool to trigger Chengying, and a wild combo enabler in some very strange lines. You can also use 1 Rota to make Yazi, use Yazi to pop a card and Yazi, Yazi effect to summon another Swordsoul and make Baxia, remove another card (s if you used Taia), and you still have Baxia's other effect. I would run 2 - this card very occasionally comes up going first and is a crucial tool on every later turn.  Omega and Savage are a package deal. Omega does literally everything but ever affect the field - that's not technically true, it occasionally beats over a monster. But the card A) attacks the hand, B) can provide information, C) recycles banished cards into the graveyard (including face-down ones?), D) recycles cards in the GY back into your deck and E) because of a quirk of THAT effect can also function as GY hate? Oh yeah, and there's no HOPT on there. Anywhere. Why is this card legal? Savage is also extremely good, and unless you have something specific to recover you should be making Savage when Halq is in the bin, especially since that's a play that protects a potential Chengying.  2 Chixiao are in the extra deck. This card immediately plusses you on summon, and then is a half-decent on-field negate after that. You need 2 because you're making this card right away and need a second for follow-up. If you ever need more, you can use Omega, although Omega can only recurr so much.  1 Baroness de Fleur. Omni-negates are good. Popping cards is good, although popping your own cards doesn't come up in this build as much as I expected. The tag-out is also wild in this deck - for example, it revives a DPE that has been Kaijued, as well as potentially Yazi and/or Baxia with are both insane targets too in their own right. It also lets you repeatedly set up the negate.  I'm on 2 Chengying, because I love this card. The rule for this card is simple - you need at least 1 way to trigger him, 1 way to protect him (not Chixiao, we're talking Solemn, Baroness, or Savage)... and then at least 1 extra. In other words, if Chixiao is the only way to trigger him, but I also have Savage and Solemn, I make Chengying - if it's Blackout and Chixiao but no negate, I make Baroness. This card is nuts, it's almost a floodgate against a lot of decks, it is a crazy powerful interruption if you use your brain, and the card also beats over everything and is a decent wall in Defense Mode too... oh yeah, and also it has generic protection too, for reasons that are good. the card does a lot. However, don't play into Nibiru, it really isn't worth it. Oddly, Baroness is sometimes just flat-out worse than Chengying, so even though I've stressed this play pattern, I also want to point out, when you have a secure Chengying, freaking make Chengying, because at that point you're narrowing down the lines of counterplay even further.  Still perpetually tuning - changed the P.U.N.K. package around to try and reduce some of the frequency of those bricky hands. While they were very soft bricks, I just don't think a deck that runs Deskbot as a true Takatomborg, as well as Destiny Hero monsters for Fusion Destiny, can afford the Gabu package, even though it was typically pretty good at mitigating the disadvantage from Foxy Tune.  Forever tuning. After a brief foray into the Rose Dragon package, I ultimately decided to stick to just PUNK, Tenyi, Swordsoul, Halq, and DPE (that's enough pile IMO). I just needed some of those generic staples back into the main, and so this version is tuned to do a little better going second. It bricks slightly more often, but also has play way more often, so I prefer this version.

deck_name: Raidraptor (Pure Raidraptor monster in extra deck)
deck_excerpt: To win the game by Raidraptor only! 3 Ultimate Falcon will give a big surprise to your opponent! When bad hand, next game use KaLi YuGa to win the gam
deck_description: I use this deck and got the top5 on the 43 people weekly tournament last month. The goal of this deck is to make the 3 Ultimate Falcon boards. (require 2 rank up magic in hand). 1 rank-up magic can make 1 to 2 Ultimate Falcon for final boards. 0 rank up can make 0 to 2 Ultimate Falcon for final boards. The final board has 3 Ultimate falcons which all are unaffected by other card's effect, 1 to 2 booster Strix on hand to protect the Ultimate Falcon destroyed by battle, or 1 booster Strix and raidraptor-readiness to avoid all the damage in turn 2. To make the ultimate falcon, there are 3 +1 ways. First is to make the rank 7, and use it and another raidraptor to link wise strix, when rank 7 send to the grave, it can special summon 1 ultimate falcon from the extra deck. The second is to use last strix or cattle to make the rank 8 satellite cannon falcon, then use astral rank up or skip force to make the ultimate falcon. Third is to use the phantom knights' rank-up-magic force to make the ultimate falcon.  1 way that is not common to use is when rank 5 destroyed and sent to grave, bringing back the ultimate falcon from the grave. To make the rank 7 Arsenal Falcon(Key Card for this deck), there are 2 + 2 ways. First way is use any 2 level 4 raidraptor to make raider's knight, then use effect to make rank5 stranger falcon, then use astral rank up or skip force make rank 7. Second way is use cattle or last strix make rank 6, then use raid force or phantom knights' rank up magic launch to make rank 7. Another 2 uncommon wat to make rank 7, one is to use cattle or last strix to make rank5, the use astral or skip rank up to make rank7, one is to use phantom knight's rank up magic force to make rank7(this will block wise strix for the rest of the turn), those siuation usually happen when start with not good hand, or be blocked some step by handtrap. To make rank 4 force strix, just remember the basic all level 4 raidraptor effect, how to extend basic on the hand, usually start with vanish vanishing Lanius or tribute Lanius or last strix. Then speical strangle lanius or fuzzy lanius or pain lanius to make rank 4 or link 2. (Remainder* Strangle lanius has limit for the Dark monter for the rest of the turn, Fuzzy lanius has limit for the "Raidraptor" monster for the rest of the turn, Pain lanius use for xyz only can use for wing beast xyz monster, raider's wing used effect to speical summon will banish when it leaves the field.) To win the game in turn 3, firstly keep at least 1 Ultimate Falcon with xyz material(it can detach 1 material to block opponent all card effect for the rest of the turn), then use Rank-Up-Magic Skip Force in the grave, banish it, and 1 raidraptor monster in the grave, reborn 1 raidraptor xyz monter from the grave.(usually keep 1 of your opponent monster attack at least 2500, then reborn rank 5 stranger falcon, suicide attack that monster, when stranger falcon destroyed by battle or effect and send to the grave, it can reborn 1 raidraptor monster from the grave, then bring back the rank 7 on the grave, and suicide attack that monster, then rank 7 destroyed and send to the grave, use rank 7 effect to bring the rank 12 final fortress falcon from the extra deck, use rank 12 to attack, when rank 12 attack destroys the opponent monster, it can banish the raidraptor xyz monter from the grave and attack again, this effect can use at most twice which means at most 3-time attack with 3800 attacks. ) Another way of this deck is to use 2 heel eagle change 2 fuzzy Lanius to avoid "Raidraptor" monster limit, then make Phantom knight Rusty search rank up magic launch, and use gagagaga magician reborn the rank 7 on the grave, then make KaLi YuGa in opponent's turn. Common Handtrap Part Ash: only force Strix or the mimicry Lanius or fuzzy Lanius will be affected by ash, for the effect, special summon from the deck by wise Strix, it can use a self chain to avoid ash, witch is chain 1 wise Strix, chain 2 fuzzy Lanius or Arsenal Falcon effect in the grave. Infinite or Effect veiler: depends on which step when your opponent uses. Usually use some not the most important effect first, then see if they use any of these effects. Nibiru:  The biggest challenge for this deck, has two ways to avoid, one is to make the Arsenal Falcon in 5 steps (require rank up magic in hand), and another one is to make the ultimate Falcon first(also require rank up magic in hand), then detach material to avoid all the card effect until the end of your turn. Psy Gamma and Ghost Orge: Also depends on which step they use, but they always use for first effect or wise Strix effect, then check the hand if there are more monster special summons. Ghose Belle: only works on the Arsenal Falcon, if this is not use the rank up from the wise Strix search, make the second one by wise Strix to get the second rank up magic. ...And there are more and more handtrap for the game, if you can not over, just start a new game! My deck is not perfect, but the meaning of the monster is uneffected by any card effect is really good for the environment now, just avoid the kaiju and the monster can increase attack! Hope this is helpful to you.

deck_excerpt: Popular DB deck meets Master Duel.
deck_description: Hi guys!  I’m here with another master duel list, this one is for mekk-knights!  Normally Blue Sky would be at two but Girsu is a limited card in master duel and so I rolled with three to be better at searching.  This particular list aims to go second, it’s entire idea is to otk with big bodies because that’s what mekk-knights are but if it can’t do that it’s other job is to use Key, Whispers, and Secret to preform a lockdown.  People in master duel don’t play around mekk-knights.  Mekk-Knights have four animated monsters!  Purple Nightfall as the leader of the Mekk-Knights and the strongest one stats-wise while they are separated (nightfall also is probably the best one, period).  Blue Sky is a monster who serves importance in the storyline choosing a successor and other things, he’s also a pretty solid card too who can provide three searches.  Spectrum Supreme, the monster who basically is when all of the Mekk-Knights combine into one.  And Avramax, who is just a Mekk-Knight for lore reasons.  Overall, very fun! Would recommend if you want to see how bad players are at reading!

deck_excerpt: An OTK focused Cyber Dragon Deck with the Cyberdark engine.
deck_description:
So, this is Version 2 of my Master Duel CyDra Deck, made after the release of the Cyberdark Structure Deck. It is still OTK focused with some things to do going first. The cards:
  • Jizukiru: A searchable Kaiju that you can fuse away for Fortress Dragon.
  • Cyber Dragon: The original. Easy monster on the field going second, the target for Machine Duplication, can out stuff like Apollousa/Mechabe via the Chimeratechs.
  • Galaxy Soldier: A machine Lv5 for Nova and a LIGHT Lv5 for Pleiaden. With him and a Herz on hand you get a full Nova with a Cyber Dragon in GY to revive (Soldier send Herz to special > CL1 Soldier add another Soldier, CL2 Herz add a CyDra > Send CyDra to special the second Soldier > Overlay into Nova/Pleiaden). Only at 2 because you can only search OPT with it so the 3rd one tends to be dead. Searchable with Cyber Repair Plant.
  • Cyberdark Chimera: Part of the Cyberdark Engine. Searched via Cyberdark Realm, you can send a Spell from Hand to GY to search Power Bond and you can also fuse from GY for that summon. Very easy OTK, but pretty disruptable.
  • Cyberdark Claw: You can discard it to search for either Cybernetic Horizon or Cyberdark Realm. It is also a material for Cybernetic Horizon to send to grave. Only 2 because you don't need a 3rd.
  • Maxx "C": Master Duel Tax. I wish it were banned.
  • Cyber Dragon Core: Searches every Spell/Trap, starts your combos, is a CyDra in GY and on Field, can be searched by Emergency and Repair Plant, is a target for Machine Duplication and can be banished from GY to special a CyDra-Monster from Deck when you have no monsters. Very susceptible to Ash/Imperm.
  • Cyber Dragon Nächster: Great extender and good for recovery. You can send a CyDra to GY to immediatley revive it. You can also revive Nova/Infinity or Rampage Dragon. Very searchable and can be specialed by Core for recovery. Is a target for Machine duplication.
  • Cyber Dragon Herz: Searches a CyDra from Deck or GY(which includes Nächster/Core due to their effects) when it is sent to GY (either by Contactfusing it, as material for Soldier/Nächster/Droplet). Can also become a Lv5 when specialed. A Machine Duplication target.
  • Cyberdark Realm: Searches Chimera (or Claw if need be) and gives you a free Normal Summon. Can be searched by either Claw or Core.
  • Cyber Emergency: Searches every CyDra and can be recovered if the activation(!) is negated. Searchable with Core.
  • Cyber Repair Plant: Searches a LIGHT Machine when you have at least 1 CyDra in GY. Is used for Soldier and Jizukiru and can be searched by Core.
  • Cybernetic Horizon: An insane searcher. Gives you either part of the Cyberdarks/CyDras (whatever you need), can activate Herz and sends a Cyber-Fusion to GY, which is also important for the OTKs. Only at 2 because it can be dead quickly and is searchable with either Claw or Core.
  • Machine Duplication. Gives you 2 CyDras on the Field when you have Core/Nächster/Herz. So you get a very easy Nova -> Infinity with it. It's not OPT(!).
  • Overload Fusion: Great Recovery, can be used to extend into Rampage after a combo.
  • Power Bond: Enables insane OTKs. Can be searched and 'powered up' with Chimera.
  • Called by the grave: To stop Ash/Maxx "C"/DPE/etc.
  • Cyberload Fusion: Can be searched with Core, works great together with Chimera/Overload. It's a quick-play, so you can use it in the Battle Phase for  e.g. Twin Dragon to push for game.
  • Forbidden Droplet: A must-have going second. Also triggers Herz.
  • Cybernetic Overflow: Great disruption when you have to go first. Searchable with Core
  • Infinite Impermanence: A great trap, works from your hand when your field is empty, but is not dead when you have to go first.
  • Cyber Eternity Dragon: Your primary target for Cybernetic Horizon. It protects your OTK by banishing it from GY. Can also be used as a wall in a pinch.
  • Chimeratech Megafleet Dragon: Removes monsters from the Extra Monster Zone, great to remove Arrival-Cyberse/Apollousa
  • Invoked Mechaba: You can summon it with Nova when your opponent Nibirus you.
  • Chimeratech Overdragon: As a comeback option with Overload Fusion.
  • Cyber Twin Dragon: Mostly summoned with Cyberload Fusion during the Battle Phase to push for game.
  • Chimeratech Fortress Dragon: To remove hard to remove machines like Superdora.
  • Chimeratech Rampage Dragon: Your primary OTK-enabler. Destroys enemy backrow and can attack up to 3 times by milling 2 monbsters from deck. Thats 12600 Damage with Power Bond.
  • Cyber Dragon Infinity: An omni-negate for going first or to protect your OTK. Can also be used to suck up annoying enemy monsters.
  • Constellar Pleiaden: As another disruption when you go first.
  • Cyber Dragon Nova: Bridges into Infinity, revives a CyDra and can push for OTKs. Also punishes your opponent for sending it to the GY.
  • Cyber Dragon Sieger: Boosts your OTK-enablers like Rampage or Twin.
  • Salamangreat Almiraj: To link of Core to make Repair Plant live.

Gusto is a terrible archetype, full of "When" conditions that easily miss timing, cards that barely work together, split between the animals being Winged Beast-Types, and the humans being Psychic-Types, the cards are a relic of Yu-Gi-Oh's past. However, people have tried to make them work by using the glue archetype for the Beast Tri-Type, Tri-Brigade, which improves the deck drastically, but still doesn't make the deck viable by any means. Great if you want to troll or have fun though.  For the decklist, we have a Gusto package of 2x Wind Channeler, 2x Caam, 2x Pilica, 2x Vedir, 1x Sphreez, 1x Laplampilica, and 1x Gulldos, we have a Tri-Brigade package of 3x Fraktall, 3x Kerass, 3x Kitt, 3x Nervall, 2x Revolt, 1x Shuraig, 1x Rugal, 1x Bearbrumm, and 1x Ferrijit, for the rest of the Main Deck, we have my preferred Handtrap lineup of 2x Nibiru, 3x Ash Blossom, 2x Ghost Belle, 2x Veiler, and 3x Imperm, 1x Barrier Statue of the Stormwinds, 2x Tenki(if it were at 3 we would play 3x), 1x Avarice, 1x Called By, and 3x E-Tele, for the rest of the Extra Deck, we have 1x Baronne, 1x Clear Wing Synchro, 1x Formula Synchron, 1x Underworld Goddess, 1x Doom Eagle, 1x Halqifibrax, and 1x Double Dragon Lords

deck_name: Zombie World Skull Servants Post DIFO
deck_excerpt: Zombie World if going first, Skull Servants if going second.
deck_description: This deck uses 2 zombie strategies with each one excelling over the other depending on if you are going first or second. If going first, your objective is to set the classic generic Zombie combo: get both Zombie World and Crystron Halqifibrax on the field, summon Glow-Up Bloom with Halq's effect, link Bloom off and use it's graveyard effect to summon Doomking Balerdroch since you control Zombie World, then link your link 1 and Doomking off into Vampire Sucker, so in your opponent's turn you will get a draw from Sucker when Doomking comes back, plus once you used Doomking's effects you can use Halq to go into Formula Synchron to draw another card and then use both Formula and Doomking to synchro summon Baronne de Fleur. The nice thing about the Skull Servants is that they also have use turn 1 as extenders for your combo (Both Wightprince and Wightmare can summon bodies on to the field) while helping you clean things up in turn 3 with a King of the Skull Servants that is easily 5000+ ATK in most cases. If going second, the utility of the Skull Servants doesn't really need an explanation, they are one of the more iconic go second decks in the game, all they really need is to get Wightbaking into the grave to get things started and this deck has many ways to do so. The deck also runs Super Polymerization and Forbidden Droplet which are not only great for breaking boards going second and discarding the cards you want in grave but can also be set if going first. Lastly I want to cover the Assault Mode package that I play, 3 Emergency Teleport and One for One are used to go into Psi-Reflector, which is used to go into level 8 synchros without the need to use your normal summon which you'd rather use on Uni-Zombie/Shiranui Solitaire; Chaos Ruler, The Chaotic Magical Dragon can help you get out of situations where your hand isn't good enough to get your graveyard dumping started, while Skeletal Dragon Felgrand, the other level 8 synchro we play, is mostly a go second card, as it banishes an opponent's monster from field or grave on summon, to make this with the Assault Mode cards we need Zombie World on the field however, as it requires a zombie tuner.
https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=galW2N4fhk8&t=25s

deck_excerpt: When your luck is as hot as the heart of the cards
deck_description: This is the deck that will make you say, "Just my fuckin' luck...". Spells and Trap heavy deck that all orient around chance that rely on delaying your opponent and chip away their LP towards victory. The game starts as soon as the first coin flip happens to give you the moral and the better chance to win Gambler is in your starting hand to refresh your hand after your first move. Second Dice Roll is a must have to increase your chance to get the results you want and to avoid the negative repercussions of getting the wrong call, especially with Gambler. Its high risk, high reward at the beginning of the duel. Consider your monster cards as your opponent's dealer. Ms. Judge and Dice Jar forces your opponent to test their own luck. If their luck is as shitty as yours, you can cripple your opponent's monster field to keep yourself alive. The Paths of Destiny and Head Judging also makes your opponent to test their luck and to deal good damage if luck is on your side. Tour of Doom, Fairy Box, and Roulette Spider should be considered as your last line of defense. Having That Six should only be used to rig the result of Dice Jar's outcome and use the maximum potential of it's effect. By changing your dice result to a 6, you deal 6000LP without relying on luck. There are a few things to consider while using this deck that the cards don't make clear; - Second Coin Toss only works once, and only once. It can't be used on multiple cards that has a coin flip effect. - Against decks that can kill spells and traps or cards like Harpies' Feather Duster or Lightning Storm is this deck's weakness since there's no defense against them. - Activating Second Coin Toss after activating The Paths of Destiny also give your opponent the chance for another coin toss. - Use Dicephoon before placing down any cards if by the off chance that your roll a 5 and must destroy one of your spell/trap card after destroying your opponent's. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9__fRBhRzXM

deck_excerpt: Well I have asked this before but, did you guys really think that Dinos would go extinct?
deck_description:
I believe that the strategy of the deck is fairly simple as happens with most trap decks. Practically the goal is to bring out your two boss monsters, Dinomorphia Kentregina and Dinomorphia Resturm, as soon as possible. An easy way to do this is the following:
  1. Normal summon Dinomorphia Therizia
  2. Activate Therizia's effect and set from the deck to the field the trap card Dinomorphia Frenzy
  3. During your opponent's Main Phase you activate Dinomorphia Frenzy to fusion summon Dinomorphia Kentregina (I usually send as materials Dinomorphia Stealthbegia from the Extra Deck and Dinomorphia Diplos from my Main Deck)
  4. Activate Kentregina's effect to banish Frenzy from the GY and replicate it's effect. The target of this fusion summon is your Dinomorphia Rexsturm
At this point of the game you have halved your LP twice meaning that thanks to Rexsturm's effect your opponent's monsters with an ATK value of 2000 or more points cannot activate their effects. However it's almost a given that you will be given the chance to lower your LP even more, making Rexsturm even more deadly. Overally a pretty intersting deck with a unique type of gameplay, that in my opinion should see more play competitevely (if this already happens please forgive me).

deck_excerpt: Will this deck see glory again?
deck_description: Guys if you expected me to analyze how this deck plays, then sorry but you clicked the wrong deck profile Instead I will state my reasoning for some of my choices Non Handtrap Cards Jack Jaguar (2off) - Pot of Desires: In my opinion the ratio of your Jaguars is always based on Desires. Builds that don't use Desires can play only 1 Jaguar, but I have some kind of masochistic relationship with that card (it's complicated I can't explain) so I can't help but using it. Since we always want our copy of Jaguar when playing the deck I opted for the classic 2off to secure at least a copy in case I use Desires Flame Bufferlo (instead of Lady Debug): I feel like I don't really need to explain this but I'll do it. With 3 Cynet Minings and 3 Salamangreat Circles I think there is no need for Debug. Bufferlo instead offers 2 new cards when linked away (providing we manage to use his effect) which in my opinion is of much importance since those 2 cards may be extends (Parallel Exceed for instance), handtraps or Called-by. Accesscode Talker (2off): I know some of you are wondering about that choice. Well it's a way to ensure your final attack will surely pass through, meaning that it's just a consistency choice as it is with @Ignisters. That's also the reason I decided to play 1 Heatleo instead of the classic 2. Dark Ruler No More (3off - Side Deck): Drnm, as this card's name is abbreviated is arguably one of the best (if not the best) going 2nd cards in the game for this format. People could say that Droplet has a bigger impact. That's not wrong but please let me explain even if you think it is wrong. So Salamangreat being mostly a control deck prefers to have cards to use for control (traps, handtraps, etc.). So with using Droplet you may have to give up on such cards. On the other hand Drnm does not cut down your hand size and is a budget card nowadays thanks to it's most recent reprint. My reasoning may be wrong in this choice, so if you have some other idea please do explain in the comments (by using arguments not like some screaming chimpanzees). Rivarly of the Warlords (3off - Side Deck): Another card that allows controlling the game. If we exclude Bagooska all your monsters that can exist on our field are Cyberse so we are not largely affected. To be honest the debate here lies within the dilemma of using Rivarly or Gozen Match. My reasoning of using the former is the fact that it can shutdown engines like Brave, P.U.N.K or Therion when used in decks of not the same type which is usually the case. Handtraps Any proper player should know that the handtraps used in a deck are chosen based in the decks you will face in the tournament you are going to participate or your friends' decks if you play more casually. Nevertheless there are handtraps like Ash Blossom and Effect Veiler who have a big impact on both combo and control decks. So I will refrain from explaining why I am using these 2 and instead explain my reasons for the other hts included D.D. Crow: This particular handtrap is a good budget option for most recent formats. Nowadays with the Scythe lock still being around and it's ability to banish any card from the opponent's GY I'm pretty sure it can bring headaches to players that like their GY Nibiru (Side Deck): Nibiru is a high impact handtrap that can make most opponents cry. The reason why I felt like I have to explain this choice of mine is the fact that in this deck is used as a control going 2nd option against combo decks which always are on high spirits. Droll & Lock Bird (Side Deck): Okay I now people will ask why to use this handtrap in a format when no Dragon Link exists. Yeah I know you guys are right and Ghost Ogre or Ghost Belle can be better choices. But, what makes me want to use Droll is the return of Monkeyboard and of course the return of the 2nd copy of Benten.

deck_excerpt: Pure P.U.N.K. build, using Jet Synchron to make Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity and P.U.N.K.s to make Psychic End Punisher or Amazing Dragon. A
deck_description: This is an attempt at a pure P.U.N.K. list, using Jet Synchron and Halq to enable Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity. This deck has two main lines: opening one of the P.U.N.K. starters with an extender (Red Hared Hasty Horse, Gizmek Orochi, or Psychic Wheeleder), or opening a P.U.N.K. starter with no extender. I didn't include Ash Blossom, Nibiru, or Crossout Designator in this list to keep it semi-budget, but I will upload another list with a more optimized build using those cards.     Our starters are Ze Amin, Sharakusai and another P.U.N.K. in hand, Emergency Teleport, Ogre Dance, or Foxy Tune. If we open Ze Amin, we search Foxy Tune after summoning, use Foxy Tune to summon Sharakusai, and continue with the combo listed below. If we open Emergency Teleport we can do the same thing, searching Ze Amin, or we can summon Sharakusai if we have a P.U.N.K. in hand. Ogre Dance searches either Ze Amin or Sharakusai, and Foxy Tune does the same. Make sure to use your Ogre Dance for a search before continuing the combo, as we will need a Dark in grave. Also, always use your Ze Amin search, grabbing Ogre Dance if we already have Foxy Tune.  Once we have Sharakusai and another P.U.N.K. in hand or on field, we want to use our extenders. First summon  Cupid Fore, then Psychic Wheeleder, if you have them. Activate Sharakusai to fusion summon Rising Carp using a monster in hand, or on field if you don't have a monster in hand. Activate Rising Carp to summon a Deer Note and a Madame Spider or Wa Gon from deck (preferably Madame Spider). If you only opened one extender, normal summon a P.U.N.K. from hand, then link off the extender and the P.U.N.K. for your Halqifibrax, using Halq to search Jet Synchron. Syncho summon Chaos Ruler using Deer Note and your other P.U.N.K. on field, activating Deer Note, then Chaos Ruler. Summon Sharakusai off of Deer Note and add a monster to hand off of Chaos Ruler (preferably a hand trap). Synch off Chaos Ruler and Jet Synchron for Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss, then use Jet Synchron in grave to return it to the field, and use Chaos Ruler's effect to return it to the field, as well.  Now, on your opponent's turn, you should have at least one trap (searched off of Madame Spider), one hand trap (from Chaos Ruler, if we're lucky), Sharakusai's ability to synch into Amazing Dragon for a few bounces, Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss's effect negation, and Halq into Formula Synchron into Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity to stop your opponent form activating cards and effects.     Our line is much less exciting if we don't open any extenders. We still make Rising Carp off of Sharakusai, but instead of going for Halqifibrax and Chaos Ruler, we make Draco Berserker of the Tenyi, summoning back Sharakusai off of Deer Note. We are playing three Pot of Avarice to shuffle back our P.U.N.K.s; specifically Rising Carp, which we can use on following turns to make another Amazing Dragon or Psychic End Punisher. If we get Ash Blossomed, we can sometimes still extend a bit. Gossip Shadow is in the deck to allow for followup after getting Ashed on our Ze Amin/E-Tele/Foxy Tune as long as we have a Psychic Wheeleder and a Lv 3 P.U.N.K. in hand. If we know that the opponent is playing Nibiru, and we open Psychic Wheeleder and an Emergency Teleport or Foxy Tune, we can make Gossip Shadow before committing to our Draco Berserker line.     With a Red Hared Hasty Horse, we can instead make Chaos Ruler or Draco Berserker, and with Gizmek Orochi we can make a level 11 instead. Satellite Warrior is in our extra deck so that if we get stuck on Halqifibrax with a level 8 on field or a Gizmek Orochi in grave, we can make Satellite Warrior off of our Formula Synchron summon. Unfortunately, without Crossout Designator we don't have much play through Nibiru. If you have any ideas on what would help this deck to survive a Nibiru, please comment down below.     That's all I have for this deck, I hope you like it and please let me know if there are any changes you would make!

deck_description: Draw, draw and draw. Tip: -Summon 2 Live★Twin first, then Summon Huggin Search Spring, then Summon Ki-sikii and Draw 1. -If you can't Summon Sunny, Summon Frost and Huggin Search Spring then Ki-sikii (or make sure you have Ki-sikii on the Field and Frost in the Grave). You often Draw 1 in Opponent's Turn. -Active Point in Draw Phase to avoid Droll. -If your opponent have more than 1 card on the field, don't Summon Ki-sikii on 5th Monster Zone, to Summon Unicorn Colink Ki-sikii Suffle 1 and Draw 1, then Summon Lil-la and Destroy 1. If they only have 1 card, don't Summon Lil-la on 1st Monster Zone (to Suffle 1 and Draw 2). -Snitch is a very good Card to survive OTK but if Opponent can't, don't Active too soon. -If Opponent have Raigeki/Storm/Duster, Tribute Sunny and Summon Huggin to protect your Field and Draw 1. -Underworld is another boss beside Sunny and can be used to remove unaffected Monster. Side deck: -Go first: Remove Psy packet and some useless card then Side Judgment and some suitable card (usually Nibiru/Cosmic/Droll). -Go second: Remove Evil★Twins Ki-sikii & Lil-la and Challenge (Combo Deck)/Psy packet (Control Deck) and some useless card. -If some Mysterune Quick-play is useless, remove 2 then Side 1 Slumber.
