deck_excerpt: Pretty viable deck for Master Duel ranked
deck_description:
Going first deck, You can customise your hand-traps so that Cross-out Designator is able to negate more cards, You can opt for a Hot Red Dragon win condition or Archlord Kristya. You can brick sometimes. I wanted to keep this short so I left out many specific interactions between cards that you should look out for. I've been optimising and playing this deck since Master Duel was released.   Goals: Dump as much of deck as possible into GY to activate effects and summon multiple negates.   Step 1: Checking for and playing around hand traps: Bait out hand traps with low value cards.
  • Use danger engine to bait out ash-blossom as their effect is not once per turn
  • If you have Psy-Framegear Gamma in hand, try to bait out hand-trap into free Chaos Ruler
  • Charge of Light Brigade discards cards even if the search is negated
  • You have 10 cards which counter Maxx C
  • Normal summon Raiden is good for checking for hand-traps
  Step 2: Get out Chaos Ruler or Curious Chaos Ruler is better summon, only Curious if you are unable to go into Chaos Ruler first. I usually summon Curious with 3 different dark monsters Curious can send:
  • Felis to the GY to set up for Borreload Savage Dragon (Most cases)
  • Starliege Seyfert to get Levianeer from GY (if Felis cannot be sent to GY)
  • Fairy Tail Snow for more material for Link Summons and disruption on opponents turn
  Step 3: Summon Main Negates
  • Link Curious into Apollousa (usually for only 2 Monster Negates, the maximum 4 is overkill), so that there is a Link Monster in GY for Borreload Savage Dragon
  • Summon Borreload Savage Dragon
If you still have extra resources:
  • Go into I:P Masquerena for Underworld Goddess and tribute opponents monster on their turn
  • Go into Halqifibrax to summon Forumla Synchron and then Big red synchro dragon
  • Go into Archlord Kristya if you are running that win-con
This is a basic end board that you want to achieve, however this deck has many different paths depending on draw and GY rng, you will have to play this deck for a long time to figure out all the possibilities. HF

The core combo  The core combo is to normal summon either infinitrack harvester or machina metalcruncher then using their on summon effects to search for infinitrack brutal dozer then you use the effect of brutal dozer to tribute your harvester or metalcruncher to special summon it self to then use its effect to summon infinitrack trencher from the deck. The you want to overlay them to XYZ summon infinitrack river stormer you then use stormers effect to detach and search for Therion "King" Regulus you then use King's effect to summon himself and to equip the harvester or metalcruncher in your gy to him (This is your fifth summon so you have avoided Nibiru). Also with some hands you don't want to search king for example if you have a revolving switchyard in your hand you would rather search derricrain or if you have detticain in your hand you would like to search for bullet. But continuing with the king line you would link off the river stormer for a goliath and activate the effect of trencher in your gy to bring back the brutal dozer you then link off dozer for goliath the link off both goliaths for an ancient gear ballista to search for an ancient gear bot which will then search for the infinitrack tunneller. Then you activate the tunneller tribute the ballista to summon itself then link off the tunneller for a goliath and use the gy effect of river stormer to tribute the goliath to summon itself(Don't use goliaths effect) then activate the effect if tunneller in gy to shuffle the brutal dozer, the three goliaths and the ancient gear ballista into the deck to draw two cards, that's the core combo the rest depends on your hand and what you draw the main thing is that your always looking for a way to summon number 81 with a derricrain attacked to it as effectively an unaffected zoodiac drident.

deck_excerpt: A Normal/Rare rarity deck for Yu-Gi-Oh! Master Duel. Adds in a Paleozoic engine to allow greater board control and trigger the effect of Pacifis, The
deck_description:
The deck lives and dies by the field spell, Pacifis, The Phantasm City; consequently, 3 copies of it and a searcher, Planet Pathfinder, are used. Pacifis has two primary effects:
  1. When a Normal Monster is summoned, search for a "Phantasm Spiral" card
  2. After the resolution of an opponent's card effect, Special Summon a lvl 8 Normal token to your field
Search the Phantasm Spiral trap cards to control the field and take victory. Phantasm Spiral equip cards help summon the 2900 Attk Phantasm Spiral Dragon to push for that extra bit of damage, and  Cardcar D gives draw power. The Paleozoic trap cards not only assist in controlling the field, but also count as Normal monsters when Summoned from the graveyard, and thus can trigger Pacifis' effect to search for a Phantasm Spiral card. Fists of the Unrivaled Tenyi operates as a powerful omni-negate, and should your opponent destroy it, Summons a 4500 Attk Blue-Eyes Ultimate Dragon from the deck. Sea Stealth Attack not only recycles and protects your field spell, but banishing your token as a response to opponent card effects guarantees a Pacifis search, and it also provides a destruction effect during battle for your lvl 8 token and Phantasm Spiral Dragon. The Extra Deck should almost never be used, as it locks you out of the Phantasm Spiral card effects. Use only as a toolbox when absolutely necessary.

deck_excerpt: The magic that put the Pendulum summoning mechanic on the map during Master Rule 4 comes back to competitive status, and holds itself up just fine.
deck_description: Gameplay video in the link down below - Exo ( https://youtube.com/watch?v=v42WZKl94IY&feature=youtu.be )   If things aren't what they truly used to be, then we are officially at that point where we ascend into means of further extending beyond our reaches. One thing is clear that it is the norm to not try to innovate what can be fixed; but sometimes, old norms need to be broken in order for new habits to be instated for the sake of progressing new ideas. That being said we have reached a point to where Pendulums have a chance to make a comeback in Yu-Gi-Oh's already tragic metagame. One full of chaos and disray; one full of cynicism and calamity; but also a metagame where it's not one deck or the other. Just as the "supposed tier 0" deck that feeds off the darkness by taking advantage of Super Polymerization, and it's fusion caliber to maximize the playing field with negates, disruptions, and all other annoyances; but only to be thwarted by all others by it's own tools.   Now that the dust has settled and the dragon has been slained, the Pendulum Magicians can take it's course to do all it can to retake their place, even though they lost what was once their former power harnessed from a span of over 5 years. In contrast, the first of these pieces to make a comeback from their downfall of Performapal Monkeyboard; however, the problem lies in it being at only 1 copy per a deck and given that I couldn't draw it out entirely or make proper use of it during my test runs, I recommend not playing it until it at least gets back at 2 or even back at unlimited status (considering that Plushfire will less likely ever come off the banlist at all). Arguably you can search Monekyboard out with Performapal Skullcrobat Joker and go from there; but I argue that he has better targets (such as Double Iris Magician and Performapal Celestial Magician). Regardless, this is a card that has just got off the banlist and has already circulate its preferences from many other players who had different experiences and opinions with the card firsthand, so I will take it with the grain of salt instead.   Next I made some slight changes to the lineup with the addition of the Symphonic Warrior package over Scythe Lock. The reason for this is the need for 0/0 Pendulum scales to make consistent Pendulum summons more frequent if I do not have Oafdragon Magician at hand, or if I tend to need to him to go into Baronne de Fleur. Now in this case, I also made it clear it could also be a justification that I could take the opportunity to test the new Synchro monster Symphonic Warrior Rockks; as on summon he can recover a Pendulum Monster (such as Harmonizing Magician) from your Extra Deck to your hand, and can be placed in the Pendulum Zone if destroyed by battle/card effect. Also can retain the effect of the Pendulum monster recovery from the Extra deck (during the stand-by phase), but can pop itself and 1 monster that declares an attack during your opponents battle phase. It's a fun addition I wanted to do, not to give the cards any real attention or to inflate their sedimental value with hype through arrogance or over eagerness; but just an experiment I wanted to work with.   Then comes the newly released link-2 monster, Beyond the Pendulum that allegedly was supposed to be a step up in replacing the former Heavymetalfoes Electrumite. What I do have a problem with here is that while it does a decent job in doing what Electrumite tries to do (which is generic searching for a pendulum monster); but it locks you out of monster effects of all kinds, unless you pendulum summon during the turn you summon this card. Which means that unless you wanna pass this off and just search for any Pendulum monster to prepare for Next turn plays, you aren't exactly gonna hesitate to rush in and play Beyond the Pendulum immediately into Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians or into Accesscode Talker. To be fair though it does a good job on it's own if you play her right, and I give it the benefit of the doubt that I expect her to see play alongside Heavymetalfoes Electrumite if he comes off the banlist in the future.   Finally I wanna talk about the other stuff I have, regardless if I have or I haven't used them. First and foremost, there was a newly acquitted TCG exclusive Pendulum Fusion monster released in the most recent set know as Patissciel Couverture, which can place itself in the Pendulum Zone if destroyed, and can place ANY other pendulum monster from the Extra Deck in the Pendulum Zone that is face up in the Extra Deck (made possible all thanks to the infamous fusion card, Instant Fusion). Next comes another recent release from the same set known as Psychic End Punisher, Which (at a cost of 1000LP) can banish up to 2 monsters on the field (1 from each side); can also be unaffected by your opponents activated effects if your LPs are lower than theirs; and can gain Attack points equal to the LP difference between both duelist during the battle phase. Then we have Majester Paladin, the Ascending Dracoslayer and Timestar Magician: both being Rank-4 XYZ that are useful for being generic searchers, usually used to search out components to expand further Link/Synchro plays that are needed.

deck_excerpt: Pure zombies with Vampires and Zombie World
deck_description: The basic idea is to turbo out Doomking Balerdroch/Zombie World and to support him with whatever resources you have left over--this is usually either Baronne de Fleur, Vampire Voivode/Domination, or Apollousa. Your extra is pretty much a toolbox for remaining cards or going second.  You really want to see Uni-Zombie, Vampire Ghost, and Vampire's Domain in your opening hand. Vampire Ghost+most Vampire cards typically means you can end on Beatrice to send Necroworld Banshee and Doomking Balerdroch to the gy. The deck has a lot of unique interactions-Vampire Sucker+Ghost in the grave can be a quick effect 2 tribute on your opponents turn,  and Sucker draws you a card every time Doomking revives. Rivalry+Zombie World locks your opponent out of summoning.

Invoked Dogmatika is a popular control deck that aims to control the pace of the game through cards such as El Shaddoll Winda and Invoked Mechaba, as well as being able to use cards such as Dogmatika Fleurdelis, The Knighted as a non-targeting negation hand-trap. The deck has a lot of room for tinkering around with cards that can specifically help go against a variety of different decks. This deck doesn't contain a lot of complex combos but I will go over simple lines you can go through with different resources in your hand, remember that as this is a control deck, the majority of your focus will be playing the game in a way that counters your opponent, so your combo lines may differ depending on the match-up, but the majority of cases will use the lines I lay out. I'll start out with the most basic Aleister the Invoker Normal Summon Aleister The Invoker > Effect To Add Invocation > Summon Salamangreat Almiraj Using Aleister > Summon Secure Gardna Using Almiraj > Activate Invocation, Banishing Aleister + Secure Gardna > Summon Invoked Mechaba. This simple line will almost always guarantee you an Invoked Mechaba from just 1 copy of Aleister the Invoker. Aleister The Invoker + Dogmatika Ecclesia, The Virtuous Normal Summon Aleister The Invoker > Effect To Add Invocation > Summon Salamangreat Almiraj Using Aleister > Summon Secure Gardna Using Almiraj > Activate Invocation, Banishing Aleister + Secure Gardna > Summon Invoked Mechaba. Activate Dogmatika Ecclesia, The Virtuous > Special Summon Ecclesia > Activate Effect To Add A Dogmatika > Add Dogmatika Maximus. Dogmatika Maximus Effect Banishing Almiraj For Cost > Special Summon Dogmatika Maximus > Activate Dogmatika Maximus > Send Titaniklad The Ash Dragon + El Shaddoll Apkallone To The GY > Activate El Shaddoll Apkallone > Add Shaddoll Schism. This line is a really explosive set-up for the deck, netting you a Mechaba for negation, two Dogmatikas on field and a Shaddoll Schism with the material to make El Shaddoll Winda already in the GY. On top of this, the effect of Titaniklad will have an optional trigger on your end phase that will let you add a Dogmatika Fleurdelis, The Knighted to your hand for another negation tool on your opponent's turn. Aleister The Invoker + Nadir Servant Normal Summon Aleister The Invoker > Effect To Add Invocation > Summon Salamangreat Almiraj Using Aleister > Summon Secure Gardna Using Almiraj > Activate Invocation, Banishing Aleister + Secure Gardna > Summon Invoked Mechaba. Activate Nadir Servant > Send PSY-Framelord Omega > Add Dogmatika Ecclesia, The Virtuous. From this point you can just commit to the combo as explained above with Aleister the Invoker + Dogmatika Ecclesia, however keep in mind the PSY-Frame Omega you sent to the GY, you can activate its effect to put itself back into the Extra Deck and put Nadir Servant back into the deck to resent your resource usage. These are the standard lines to go through while playing this deck, however there are far more things you can do, as you have a bunch of options in your extra deck to almost act like a toolbox, like summoning Invoked Purgatrio to pick apart boards and help facilitate an OTK as it can also deal piercing battle damage. Invoked Raidjin and Invoked Augoeides are good summons off of Super Polymerization, Invoked Raidjin is good to make with something like your opponent's Baronne de Fleur or their Wind Barrier Statue if they're playing Floowandereeze. Invoked Augoeides is good in games against Branded Despia or in games where someone might be playing something like Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer, Invoked Augoeides is also a decent monster to help push for an OTK. As always, play around with the deck, understand what the meta you will be playing in will look like and give and take accordingly, realistically I could have uploaded this deck with the engine specific cards but I just wanted to show off some tech choices you can consider for your build.

deck_description: Keeping Exodia genuinely fun and rare over bland and consistent. The deck, while orientated towards defense through cards such as Swords of Revealing, Giant Soldier of Steel or Kuriboh among others as well as the underlying draw options through DM & Gaia support, is still trying to uphold the essence of adaptability that Yugi demonstrates. With this in mind, there is no clear win condition: the deck is highly opportunistic and not to be played for wins. If there is a goal, it is to find that rare duel which, after exhausting all unorthodox and goofy options, the opponent is left slack-jawed with the unsuspected Exodia in place of a deckout. Don't be afraid to ditch it for better things however: the deck is strategy-based, not Exodia-based.

I think this deck is pretty sweet. Twins give the deck some good solid grind game (and with Sunny a way to beat over monsters) whereas the Splights give the twins the generic negation and protection from hand traps that they are really lacking. I like this version a lot.  Added the Twins, it really does come up. The basic route is pretty simple, just Evil Twins things. The idea is to use Splights to set up Red + Djinn Buster + Trouble Sunny, and maybe a Carrot. However, when your Live Twin gets stopped, the Splights will also help set-up Ki-sikil or Lil-la plays, usually again back by negation. Red does a lot for the deck. Weirdly enough the deck doesn't rely that much on gigantic Splight. Honestly, I think the Splight Package is going to be very good for a very long time - even in a theoretical world where Gigantic is banned and every other maindeck card is limited, I think the package would still see play in Link or Rank 2 spam decks, and be very good.

deck_excerpt: Ice Barriers, Crystrons, Deep Sea, etc. MASTERDUEL
deck_description: Ice Barrier (2022) (Masterduel)  _________________________________________  The deck has 3 engines.  The Ice barrier protections and special summons for each other to make the rank 4 XYZs. Make Trishula Zero Dawn, going first, you'll get the field negated off Trishula Dragon of the Ice Barrier, and have a 3300 beatstick on board. Going second you get the pop three if they don't negate the summons and you are set up for their next turn when they destroy it and summon your Trishula then. Running Ice Knight and Silent Sea Nettle nearly make extending our Defender easy, Revealer makes it even easier.  ________  Deep Sea Diva into Guitar, Guitar effect to banish the top two of opponents deck, Guitar double Divas level, Synchro Prima Donna, Prima Donna effect to give one of the banished cards to the opponent hand (careful) and special summon level one Deep Sea Artisan, she can send your top deck into grave to special summon a level 4 or lower from grave (Guitar), then Prima Donna and Guitar synchro away for a Barronn de Fleur who can't be destroyed by card effects. One card combo.  __________  Crystron Halqifibrax special summons:  •Plan A >> Citree, on opponents turn, Citree effect with a level 4 in grave to make Powered Inzektron and follow up with Halq into Crystron Quandax, and Quandax into Swordsoul Champion Cheng who will off the citree play have at least +200ATK/DEF and the Opponents cards will have at least -200ATK/DEF and he will respond to any banishment with his own, also indestructible as long as you have cards in the graveyard.  •Plan B >> Defender or Hexa, Make White Aura Whale on your opponents turn using Crystron Halq into Quandax with any level four extender, or Prima Donna and the Token summoned by banishing Speaker from grave (assuming you used Speaker and 1 Ice Barrier tuner to make Halqifibrax).  If Zujin is in grave he can come back off the Defender to trigger Defenders protection from battle.  If Zujin is not in grave, Send him off with Defender, so next turn is set up for his return.  ____________  If you are able to get Ice Knight and Silent in turn 1 with any other level 4 you can Bahamut Shark into Toadally Awesome, protecting your plays keeping Ice knight on field, or hoping you had Defender of the ice barrier and your 3rd level four was Revealer to get him or Speaker to follow him up. You have the Defender and Ice knight and Toadally to send away off the Toads effect.  __________  General Wayne can get Ice Barrier to hand if you need to protect what you've got, then dump it for the one Kaiju, or get Medallion if you need specifics, or Freezing Chains if you want protection from extra deck monsters and have a play in grave.  In a tightspot, you can use Silent Sea Nettle to return any extra deck monsters or combo pieces in grave, or summon Mistar Boy to crash with the opponent, and Summon White Aura Whale from grave, or try to get Borrel Savage Dragon on the field when Mistar Boy and Halq are in grave.     _________________________________________  HANDTRAPS >> a ratio I use in every deck so far to at least compete in the meta.  2x Ash  2x Maxx-C  2x Infinite Impermenance  _________________________________________  BOARD WIPES >> must haves when all else fails  1x Feather Duster  1x Raigeki  _________________________________________  Comments :  Prior of the Ice Barrier was too slow. The larger Ice Barriers were bricks, though Raiho can work with some changes.  I haven't had the materials to try the Atlantean Prince Nebatyss with 3x Atlantean Dragoons, but what I'm doing feels consistent.  Crystal Wing Synchro is very easy to make, could trade Borrel Savage Dragon for him.  I've seen Desert Locust played, the level 9 Crystron, the Moulinglacia but I felt what I had to remove to add them wouldn't be worth the reward.  I was playing with targets for Prima Donna other than the 1* Deep Sea Artisan and 3 cards could work if you take something out for them ; Needle Fish (when sent to GY, 1 monster your opponent controls loses 500ATK), Mermail Abyssnerei (When Sent to GY, mil a card and discard a card) works well with Zujin, Speaker, and Revealer if you already have another Revealer in hand, and Hammer Shark (Opt: reduce the level of this card from *4 to *3 and special summon 1 level 3 or lower monster from your hand.)  Open to suggestions please comment if you find something cool, or want to tell me your experience with the cards!

deck_excerpt: Fill grave with Pyros. Bring them back to do other things
deck_description: A different take on my other deck, "Burning Eruption" with more emphasis on returning Monsters from the graveyard and (hopefully) more consistency.

The strategy of this deck is to get out mirrojade and dragostapellia always on first turn. There is many super-poly targets in this deck which makes it a good match up against many decks. Just like Despia Branded this deck loses to D-Barrier but Red Reboot is used to stop it although it is hard to get in hand.     This deck is built from many of the new cards from dimension force and the structure deck albaz strike.  This deck has a simple 1 card combo which ends on a board of Dragostapellia and mirrojade with bufocolia and triantis in scale with either a set retribution or a follow up with branded fusion for next turn.  This combo requires Lonefire/Scorpio and 1 monster to discard.  Normal summon Lonefire and then activate effect to summon scorpio from deck (Skip this part if scorpio is already in hand).  Activate scorpio's effect on summon to discard the monster in hand and special summon Chlamydosundew.  Use Chlamydosundews effect to fusion summon into Ambulomelides.  Activate Ambulomelides' effect on summon to add bufocolia to hand.  Activate Ambulomelides' effect to tribute itself and special cobra.  activate cobra to add branded fusion. #Update Nov 10, 2002 now that we have more access to Kashtria & new cards

The idea is to bring as many fusion as you can to take control of the field and play it your way! Hi so this is my first deck sharing, when I first saw Tearalaments, I saw infinite fusion potential. So in order to make use of it's full power before the new card updates. I've added a few core fusion in the form of predaplant, tearalaments & venom. I had a lot of fun with this deck and it's even called anti-meta by my friends (I highly doubt it's anti meta YET) So going through the Extra Deck
1. Starving Venom Predator Fusion Dragon - this will be your master negate once you've setup the whole board (both yours and your opponent) with preda counter. Even if this big fella gets taken out in your GY there will be at times one more fusion monster which you can bring back to restart or counter 2. Guardian Chimera - summon him with the effects of any of the 3 main girls of Tearalaments + Predaplant Buffolicula with Predaplant Triantis and trigger his draw effect. Although it won't have its immunity without polymerization but you will get your draw power
3. Tearalament Kaleido Heart - This will be one of your troublemakers for your opponent to keep sending something back into their deck and come back (once per turn) should he get sent to the GY. He will be your catalyst searcher to fusion summon extra by sending another tearalaments monster to the GY.
4. Starving Venom Fusion Dragon - Struggling with high attack monster? Use his effects to help you
5. Predaplant Chimeraflessia - Well this is another trickster... Always use it to manipulate atk values of your opponent monster. It may look like a worthless 2.5k atk monster buts its actually a 3.5k with a -1k penalty to your opponent monster that its attacking. This predaplant would also help you to find instant fusion once its in the grave...
6. Tearalaments Chaetocaros - She is your main catalyst of this deck to either be used as a fusion material and sent to the GY or mill some cards with the hopes to send a few cards (EG: predaplanning, any of the three girls of tearalaments) and trigger a chain effect from the GY, The only reason keeping her at 2 at the moment because you can easily bring her back because you will use her as a fusion material (always)
7.  El Shaddoll Winda - Your main special summon lock. ALWAYS summon her LAST otherwise she will lock all your fusion combos
8. Predaplant Ambulomeloides - your searcher for predaplant and also another popper to help u pop something with preda counter on opponent field
9. Tearalament Lulucaros - Waifu yes but also a very cute version of D Hero Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer with a self-revive the same turn she sends herself to the GY or just send any of her sisters from the field after you negate
10. Time Thief Redoer -Well he's here for 2 things the effects from material detach and locking any possible cards your opponent may use against you each turn
11. Predaplant Dragostapelia - YAY for preda counter disabler. Use him to disable any effect before they trigger and rack up your counters for the big dragon
12. Raider's  Knight - if you're thinking him as a placeholder why yes he's just going to sacrifice himself for Arc Rebellion....
13. Arc Rebellion XYZ Dragon - THIS IS A LAST RESORT or when you think you have the field secured for OTK purpose. I'm very 80% sure of the time you won't be using them at all the same goes for Raider's Knight

Monsters in the Deck Summary
Tearalaments will be the catalyst for fusions Predaplant will be the traps to disable synchro summon, disable effects (if Dragostapelia is present)
Shaddoll Beast is just for draw power and Winda  

So why are there pendulum monsters? In a situation where you need more monsters on field to mill the deck or be used for material, this was the best answer to it because that way should your opponent take down any of the 3 tearalaments girls, they're basically asking you to summon as many as you can to ruin the board for them
Important Magic & Trap Cards
Field Spell Pelreino, the Primal Parallel Ruined Realm - chain its effects with any tearalaments especially Kaleidoheart and you can clear 2 cards on the field (well this got limited to 1 but it will slow down the chains you can make with it)
Predaplanning - this is another one that adds problems for your opponent, if its in the GY any fusion monster u summon will allow it to be removed from play and destroy 1 card on opponent field
Tearalaments Heartbeats - a switcher Tearalament card, use wisely or just remove from the deck
Tearalaments Grief - another switcher card with a search for your trap card (this keep at least 1 in the extra deck)
Tearalaments Scream - KEEP 2 at all times (never use just 1)

deck_excerpt: Control the board with board bombs
deck_description:
Have you ever looked at your opponents board and thought "Man I'd need like a dozen board wipes to burn though all that?" Well so have I and that is the exact reason why I went though all the cards that exist and chose the best board wipes around to make this deck.   In this deck there are three (four with Extra Deck) ways to clear the opponents board. The first two need no introductions, first is the iconic Raigeki straight off the banlist and ready for some action while the other one has been off for a while and has been one of the low-key GOAT's among traps, Torrential Tribute. The third, and most searchable, is the impressive two card combo of Volcanic Scattershot + Blaze Accelerator Reload. This combo has been the heart and soul of Volcanic deck for years, being able to both build advantage for yourself and deny your opponent of board presence. Unfortunately the deck has not seen any support since 2015 and it shows. While it can get one part of the combo easily enough with Volcanic Rocket, the other half has always been the blasting power and without it you have nothing but a card filter. Fortunately Reload has an effect while in the grave to banish itself to send Scattershot to the grave and activate it's effect that way. Now we come to the question that is a mystery to all; how do we get reload into the grave consistently? This is where the power of modern cards comes in. There is three ways to get a card into you grave; from your hand, from your field, or from you deck. From your hand and field share the same issue being you need to actually get the card into you hand, so the better way is to get it out of the deck directly. This can either be achieved by self mill (taking cards from the top of your deck and sending them to grave) or by binning (taking cards directly from your deck to grave). While mill is plentiful, it is by far the worst of the two options since you may mill cards you didn't want in the grave to begin with. On the opposite side though, binning is better as you can send the exact card away but there are only an handful for cards that actually bin to begin with, let alone a spell/trap. There is exactly one card that can bin spell/trap's and that's Foolish Burial Goods. One bin card isn't nearly enough, so we need another card and one that is preferably searchable/summonable and as it turns out we have that card in the form of Curious, the Lightsworn Dominion. He's a hard to bring out, needing three monsters of the same attribute but different type, but fortunately we have a couple of combos for the boy. The Classic Combo: I did not choose to use this combo but it is perfectly viable.
  1. Normal Summon Dark Beckoning Beast > add Opening of the Spirit Gates (this can be achieved if either or is played first)
  2. Activate Spirit Gates > add Chaos Summoning Beast
  3. Use Dark Beckoning to normal summon Chaos Summoning
  4. Link away Chaos Summoning for Linkuriboh
  5. Use Spirit Gates effect >discard> special Chaos Summoning from Grave
  6. Link away Chaos Summoning for Relinquished Anima
  7. Use all three monsters on field to make Curious >effect to bin Reload
This is the old way, though still good enough if you like it. However I have found a far better, and flexible, method to create Curious using the power of Scrap
  1. Open Scrap Raptor (achievable through the use of Fossil Dig as well as Scrapyard)
  2. Use Raptor effect >destroy Raptor> add Scrap Chimera
  3. Normal summon Chimera >special Raptor from grave
  4. Link away both cards for Scrap Wyvern
  5. (IMPORTANT! YOU MUST HAVE SET A CARD BEFORE YOU PROCEED) Use Wyvern effect >summon a Scrap from grave >destroy the Scrap >summon Scrap Golem from deck >destroy set card
  6. Use Golem Effect >summon a Scrap from grave to YOUR (do not misclick or you will be very sad) field
  7. Link away to make Curious.
The reason I like this combo more is it easier to find your starter in Raptor, and when you get to the point where you could summon Curious you have other options to link to instead. In addition, normal Volcanic decks use Royal Firestorm Guards to reset the Scattershot so that it can be used again however this is not good as it uses up your normal summon and you need to have another Pyro type in your grave. With the Scrap line you can go into Daigusto Emeral to reset if you have already Scattershot. All in all, I feel this is a fun and flexible rouge deck that can easily go up again many decks.

deck_excerpt: Dragon link with Buster Blader archetype and Fallen of Albaz
deck_description:
This is your old reliable dragon link deck, but with more spice. Besides the rokket engine I am using the Buster Blader archetype to end in a more powerful board. The inclusion of the Albaz cards is for a better support and interruptions. For the dragon link part of the deck you would do the same combo to end on a Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Sphere and a Borreload Savage Dragon with typically 2 counters. Dragon link basic combo path: 
  1. Summon a lv 4 or lower Dragon
  2. Link-1 Striker Dragon
    1. Search for Boot Sector launch
  3. Summon a Dragon
  4. Link-2 Dragunity Knight - Romulus
    1. Search for Dragon Ravine
  5. Activate Dragon Ravine
    1. Discard a card
    2. Send Absorouter Dragon from Deck to GY
    3. Activate Absorouter Dragon Effect and search for Rokket Tracer
  6. Activate Boot Sector Launch
    1. Special Summon Rokket Tracer
  7. (If you manage to have another dragon on the field)
    1. Link-2 Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Sphere (Before using Rokket Tracer effect)
  8. (If you only have Rokket Tracer)
    1. Active Rokket Tracer effect to destroy a card and Special Summon Rokket Recharger
    2. Synchro Summon Borreload Savage Dragon (Depending on the card that you destroy with Rokket Tracer in this scenario that will be the amount of Counters that it will have based on the link monster in the GY.
The Buster Blader archetype is very easy to use and is good as a backup if your opponents spend all their resources to stop your dragon link combo and have a smaller hand to start their turn. Buster Blader combo:
  1. Normal summon Buster Whelp of the Destruction Swordsman
    1. Activate its effect to search for Prologue of the Destruction Swordsman
  2. Set Prologue of the Destruction Swordsman
  3. (In your opponent's turn)
    1. Activate Prologue of the Destruction Swordsman
      1. Send Destruction Sword Memories and Buster Blader, The Destruction Swordmaster (this step is cost!)
    2. Since it was cost, activate Destruction Sword Memories as part of the chain
      1. Banish Buster Blader, The Destruction Swordmaster and any dragon from the GY
    3. Resolve and Special Summon Buster Blader, the Dragon Destroyer Swordsman and Buster Dragon
And basically that's it! Even if you opponent interrupts your search, you can use Buster Whelp of the Destruction Swordsman to start your dragon link combo since it is a dragon and level 4 monster. It can be use as an interruption bait. In some cases you can manage to have Dragon Buster Destruction Sword in the GY and you can equip it to your Buster Blader, the Dragon Destroyer Swordsman with Buster Dragon and have your opponent's Extra Deck unavailable! For the Fallen of Albaz part of the deck is very simple, if you manage have Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Sphere on the field there is a cool interaction with Fallen of Albaz. Fallen of Albaz scenario:
  1. Have Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Sphere on the field
    1. Use its effect to tribute itself to send back a card to the hand
    2. Since you tribute it, his other effect will trigger in the GY to Special Summon a dragon monster from your deck.
    3. Special summon Fallen of Albaz
      1. Activate its effect, discard a card and use it to Fusion summon with an opponent's monster
I consider this scenario to be better than using Omni Dragon Brotaur as the summon from Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Sphere effect, since you can have a better board and interruptions with the branded fusion monsters. Also, if your opponent manages to use the effect of Nibiru, The Primal Being, while you have Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Sphere on the field. You will have the same scenario. You special summon Fallen of Albaz, use its effect to fusion summon with Nibiru, The Primal Being and, since it's a light you fusion summon Albion the Branded Dragon. After that is up to you to decide which other fusion you want to make. You can go straight into making Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon. A good option is Albion the Branded Dragon → Borreload Furious Dragon. Since you can use Borreload Furious Dragon effect to destroy your Albion the Branded Dragon and another card from your opponent. This will send Albion the Branded Dragon to the GY and at the End phase you can search for Branded in White to have another fusion for the next turn since you will have Fallen of Albaz in the GY. For the trap cards there's no much to say. They are self explanatory. Red Reign is a very good protection for your boss monsters since all, except links and one synchro monster, are level 8. And that's it. I have being playing a lot with this deck, its super fun and very powerful. A lot of people never expect to be locked with the Buster Blader combo.

deck_excerpt: Big stromg armur men hit real hard
deck_description:
Of course, you ht your opponent, then try to summon Claive and Excalibur (and maybe search Chance along the way) so you can otk your opponent. The main rank 4 enablers are Thousand Blades and Morning Star, so if you try to make your own heroic deck, keep in mind that you need quite a few heroics for Blades. The real important thing is all of the cards that I don't run.

Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights

The reasons that you would want to run isolde, is that it can summon a Thousand Blades from deck which, of course, is a good payoff. The issue with Isolde is that you actually need to make it before you can use it. What I mean is that, the only cards that you would actually want to use for Isolde would be non-level 4 warriors, because making a rank 4, even if it isn't the otk, has more payoff than Isolde. The reason for this is that if Isolde summons Blades, then you would need to have 3 heroics in hand to discard for Blades, otherwise you aren't getting any actual payoff from making the Isolde in the first place. One could argue that you only need 2 discards since technically that would leave you with 3 lvl 4s and Isolde herself, but the only thing that gives you over the same play in a deck that doesn't run Isolde, would be a unicorn, which also needs a discard, albeit a generic discard, leaving you in essentially the same vice. Wether you have 2 heroics or 3 in hand with the Isolde play, the issue is that more often than not, heroics are free lvl 4 extenders, and you wouldn't need to use material on the Isolde anyways. Assuming that you are in a situation where you have 2 or 3 dead heroics in hand, AND you need to get 2 Isolde material on field, that would leave you with 2 cards in hand to actually be hts or board breakers. In most match-ups, that isn't enough to win, unless it's specifically the one(s) you need, and running Isolde (which would need 4+ brick equip spells, mind you) wouldn't be able to rescue you.  

Heroic Challenger - Clasp Sword

Fun fact for all of the 2 (max) people reading this: one of the many, MANY, reasons that I've detached myself from the rest of the "heroic community" (one other player and his abusive friend) is over disputes of the usefulness of clasp sword, many of which "ended" with me getting muted after getting insulted and yelled at for about an hour because I managed to realize that Clasp has no actual place in a heroic deck. But all of my deep hatred of them aside, I can certainly understand why a new player with no heroics experience would believe that Clasp is useful, although I must admit I don't understand the staunch defense of it. The reason that I despise Clasp so much, is that it just plain isn't worth making. The reason you would play clasp is so that you could add another lvl 4 heroic extender after summoning it w/ Blades (one of 2 ways to trigger Clasp, the other being Ambush Soldier), However all that leaves you with is (assuming you have nothing unrelated) is Blades, Clasp, and a lvl 4, but if you didn't run/summon Clasp, then you would be left with Blades and whatever lvl 4 you would summon off of blades. At first glance, this seems to prove that Clasp truly does have a use. After all, it gives you another body, and since this is a rank 4 spam deck, Clasp would also be a lvl 4... ...right? It isn't. It's lvl 1. Not to mention the fact that using Blades's effect locks you into heroics for the rest of the turn, so you can't even use it for link material. Now, if any Extra-pilled fellow such as I were to explain this one of the filthy Clasp-pilled lot, I can assure you they would respond with "Clasp doesn't add a lvl 4, it adds Knuckle, then you summon Knuckle from hand with its own effect, so you can make Jarn and summon a lvl 4 from your gy." (Side note: Knuckle will usually be classified as another lvl 4 extender, but in this case you wouldn't use its 2nd effect and it would stay lvl 1) However, as my brothers have already figured out, the difference between using Clasp that way and not using it at all, is that using it gives you a spent Jarn. Filthy Claspians would argue that that is better than not running it, which while technically being true, is overlooking a few things. First and foremost, Clasp is a HARD GARNET. This means that if you draw it, it is entirely useless. And before someone can get a chance to say it, no, being a discard for Blades is not a use. Secondly, Jarn's protection won't matter that late, since most always anyone would just use anything that pops would just quickfire it on the summon of Blades, so you wouldn't be able to summon anything at all. And keep in mind that, even the people who would die on Clasp's hill would agree that Blades is the only reasonable way to trigger Clasp anyways.

Forbidden Droplet

You literally just can't afford to discard a bunch of stuff, I don't really know how to elaborate at all.   Now that I've gone through all of the things that I get lambasted for not running, I'd like to take this time to explain some of my "spicier," as some would say, deck-building choices.

Denko Sekka & Bujinki Ahashima

Yes, I know that Sekka is a thunder monster and not a warrior, just hear me out here. If you win game 1 against a backrow heavy deck, then a Sekka backed by your 15/17 hts is usually just a free win. Some of you may be wondering why I've paired Ahashima with Sekka, and that's because Ahashima is what you use Sekka for turn 3. Sekka herself may not be a warrior, but she's still a lvl 4 monster, so if you summon a lvl 4 warrior on turn 3 and make Ahashima with that and Sekka, you can still make Claive assuming you have another lvl 4 warrior in your hand. And before you ask, yes, this IS Ahashima's only use, but the ED is really open in heroic decks.

Extra Sword

I'll admit, Extra isn't important. At all. The reason that I run it is because it's the 2nd best thing to summon off of Blades after Morning Star, and given the fact that Morning Star is a 3 of with 4 searchers, I would like to have some back-up. If you would like to, you can absolutely replace Extra with anything else (unless it's one of the things I said to not play, as my word is next to law). Have fun

deck_excerpt: Shut down, then beat down. The main goal of this deck is to completely shut down your opponent's ability to summon anything, then lock down the duel w
deck_description: Shut down, then beat down. The main goal of this deck is to completely shut down your opponent's ability to summon anything, then lock down the duel with any combination of hand/field control options.  Ground Collapse, Ojama Knight, and Ojama King all terminate your opponents ability to use Main Monster Zones. Royale Decree negates all trap effects. Silent Swordsman can negate any spell card once per turn without cost. Robbin' Goblin can tear apart your opponent's hand. These pieces in any combination will severely gimp your opponent's ability to play the game.  Ojamagic is the hidden gem here. When sent to the graveyard, it allows you to add one Ojama Green, Yellow, And Black to hand which you can use to bring the big boy Ojama King out (or if you have an Ojama Red in hand, you can finesse out the Ojama Emperor himself). This effect is easily activated with Raigeki Break, Magical Hats, Gagaga Gardna or Ojama Country.  Big Shield Gardna is not only a beefy defender, but when Ojama Country is active he is a massive 4-star 2600 beater.  Raigeki Break has two uses here. The first is generic removal, but the second is discarding Ojamagic (which it can still do even if Royal Decree is in play!)  If you are feeling extra cheeky you could add in a Yata-Garasu for a cheeky little Yata-Lock

Imagine logging into Master Duel after a long day losing the coin toss to this deck and watching it go full combo and wondering why do you even exist in this world.  I built a Gem-Knight FTK deck in master duel. The deck works incredibly well.  Your job is two things, one trigger block dragon and two get Gem-Knight fusion out of your deck, once you do that take it from there and ftk them.  The backup plan is dpe pass and if you REALLY brick hard then try surrendering but most times you’ll be able to make a play of some sort.  When you ftk it’s usually this setup, 6 monsters all special summoned including a lady lapis lazuli and master diamond along with a gem-knight monster in your hand usually achievable and gem-knight fusion in your graveyard with a banish target.  What you do from there is pitch another lady lapis lazuli with the first one and use master diamond to do the same for 6000, then you use gem knight fusion fusing the gem-knight in your hand, master diamond, and lady lapis lazuli for a second master diamond, who pitches for game.  If you want you can swap out Seraphinite for another master diamond to give the deck more wiggle room but for me the first two master diamonds are usually good enough at preforming the ftk themselves.

deck_excerpt: Deck using the new Naturia support in tandem with Therion to drain your opponents resources  Updated the list and added a write up
deck_description: Use the many starters in the deck to assemble Naturia Molcricket and Naturia Camellia to create control boards with the toolbox of Naturia monsters, supplemented by the Therion engine. Extra Deck is customizable.  Updated the list and giving a more indepth explanation of my card choices  3 Naturia Molcricket and 3 Naturia Camellia - The core of the deck. Both of these cards sets up the other and are the best normal summons in the deck. Sets up your graveyard to disrupt your opponents plays. Most games begin by getting both of these cards into rotation. Camellia is also a tutor for any naturia cards by sending Naturia Sacred Tree and Molcricket can help you catch up going second.  3 Lonefire Blossom - Extra copies of Camellia. Can also be used to start your Therion engine.  2 Naturia Marron - By far the weakest starter in the deck but sometimes Marron send Molcricket is all you got. Other than that it recycles your naturias for grind games.  1 One for One - Summons Molcricket without taking your normal summon, lets you end your first turn on boards that aren't just Camellia + Regulus  1 Foolish Burial - Sets up graveyard, sends Molcricket or a therion in a pinch  3 Foolish Burial Goods - Essentially ROTA here. Sends sacred tree to search any Naturia Card  3 Therions' "Lily" Borea - You probably know why this is here. Search the field spell to get Regulus for an omni. Also can send Sacred Trees you've drawn to search.  1 Therions' "King" Regulus - Big stats, omni negate, level 8 for Dingirsu  1 Therions' Ring, The Colosseum Saucer - Searches your Regulus, pretty great in a grind game as well. Bump this and Regulus up to 2 if you want  Naturia Tool Box  2 Naturia Horneedle - This is your main source of disruption. In tandem with Camellia and Antjaw can be triggered quite a few times.  1 Naturia Sunflower - Monster negate. Pretty strong if you have Camellia, otherwise the cost is steep  1 Naturia Antjaw - Ammo for your tribute effects, could get away with running more of these but i didn't feel it was necessary  1 Naturia Rosewhip - Floodgate summonable off of Halq. Can be used to completely shut off your opponents Spell/Traps  1 Naturia Vein - Spell/trap negate. Same deal as Sunflower but can be used with Rosewhip to completely shut off Spell/Traps  These next 3 are only in the deck because their level is convenient or are pretty good extenders  1 Naturia Hydrangea - having a level 5 is nice to summon off of Molcricket if you need a synchro monster quickly. can summon itself.  1 Naturia Cosmobeet - Just wanted a level 2 tuner  1 Naturia Ladybug - The best of these three by far, I use it in my turn one combos often as link material for Seraphim Papillon. Seraphim, Beast, Regulus and Molcricket is a pretty doable setup  3 Naturia Spring Breeze - Really good spell. Is by far the best extender in the deck and can be used on your opponents turn to drop synchros. Not a single once per turn on this card.  3 Naturia Sacred Tree - Had this at 2 but it proved to be a very good card to send for costs. Its non-search effect is sometime relevant as well.  1 Called by the Grave - Getting handtrapped can sometimes turn your entire deck off. Honestly probably should cut some of the worse naturias to run a Crossout Designator package.  3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring - i just picked the first hand trap to come to mind.  Extra  Naturia Exterio - Probably never gonna summon this but its better than Gaiastrio  Baronne De Fleur - Its the best synchro monster in the game  Borreload Savage Dragon - The second best synchro in the game, although i often find myself in situations where i haven't summoned a link monster to equip to it  Naturia Barkion - Doesn't come up very often, its really here just to have another naturia name for ladybug so any of the other synchros would do this is just the least bad of them excluding beast  Naturia Beast - incredibly good and very easy to summon. often a piece in my better setups  Herald of the Arc Light - Its another omni  Sacred Tree Beast, Hyperyton - Big negate monster, my Strenae target  Dingirsu, The Orcust of the Evening Star - Cleans up the board on the crack back.  Strenae the Rikka Queen - Recycles your Camellias and Lonefires. tribute it to aromaseraphy jasmine to summon Hyperyton  Meliae of the Trees - never summoned this but i'd rather have it then not  Accesscode Talker - You know why this is here  Knightmare Unicorn - Mostly to climb into accesscode  Papillon Seraphim - Proactive way to get Molcricket back on the board. Sometimes if i already have a molcricket in rotation i'll send a Horneedle to the graveyard to summon with this  Aromaseraphy Jasmine - Not sold on this TBH, might go with Crossrose Dragon instead, much easier to summon but needs another monster in the extra as a target.  Crystron Halqifibrax - Theoretically has some pretty powerful setups, i haven't practiced them yet so i have no idea what to do here. Could always put a Jet Synchron in the deck  Cards im considering  Naturia Mantis - Might be a sideboard card for Floo but the cost kind of doesn't jive with the deck  Naturia Ragweed - Might be good if you're running more handtraps than i am and you know your opponent is running draw spells.  Naturia Stinkbug - Could potentially make you unkillable in a grind game  Crossrose Dragon - alternative to Jasmine. Needs another extradeck slot which isn't a big problem, you can do anything with the extra deck.  Periallis, Empress of Blossoms - My Crossrose target of choice, summons Borea from the grave  I:P Masquerena - You create a ton of material on your opponents turn  Apollousa - I:P Target, but i dont feel like you can summon it early enough for it to do much  Retaliating "C" - Decent handtrap, relevant typing  Contact "C" - for the Realiating search  I've considered insect stuff but i dont think theres enough synergy there, Resonance Insect has potential but i don't think theres enough Doom Dozer targets in this deck.  The other Naturia spell traps dont have Naturia in the name making them unsearchable so i don't think they're consistent enough to justify. The field spell search is okay but you dont really want the naturias in hand unless you're running mantis.  No draw spells, didn't seem necessary, the new support makes the deck Super consistent  All in all I think the new support is exactly what the deck needed. Naturia has always had a lack of enablers for their low key busted effects but Molcricket and Camellia do exactly what the deck wants. The strengths of the deck lie in being very, very consistent and adaptable but its still not very capable of power plays. I think you can win games with it, its just not easy due to nonlinear setups and having to know which Naturias are relevant in matchups. I'm very excited to play more of this deck, it might end up being my main.

deck_excerpt: My Normal Deck for Ranked, 85% winrate.
deck_description: This is the deck i've been using lately for my ranked matches. 85% winrate. This deck can handle Swordsoul, Despia, Adamancipator, and even tri-brigade thanks to numerous cards such as: A negate (Mechaba) A floodgate (Winda) A Second negate (Fleurdelis) A second floodgate (If winda goes to gy [Caliga]) etc...  This deck is easy to learn, and is one of my favorites so far! Please, leave any suggestions in the comments. ------------------------------ This deck is very linear, so I'll show an example combo to show how it works. Normal Summon Aleister the Invoker, add invocation, summon almiraj, summon secure gardna using almiraj, activate invokation and summon mechaba. Now you have a 1 card combo w/ a negate on board.  Dogmatika monsters are used as some sort of engine to get another negation on board (Fleurdelis) but also have a great sinergy w/ shaddolls (Maximus sending to gy Apkallone, etc...)  Shaddolls are used to get construct or winda quick, so its pretty useful!  If you'd like to know more about how this deck works and/or want to get reference for some combos, please join the Invoked discord server!!! they are very kind! Just search for Yugioh Deck Discord Repository and you'll have access to the archetype's discord!

deck_excerpt: Will this be the new tier 0!?
deck_description: The brand-new (still yet to be released) OCG Archetype "Kshatri-La" looks really promising. Here's my take on the deck (Based on the TCG banlist, though the only things i'd consider from OCG are Maxx "C", Dimensional Fissure and Macrocosmos) Here's the explanation of uses and ratios: 3x Kshatri-La Fenrir/Unicorn/Ogre: As of yet the only main deck Ksha monsters, they search Monsters/Spells/Traps respectively while also disrupt the opponents play by banishing cards facedown. Normally you see a 3/3/3 ratio on the lists and the reason behind that is, well... There's barely any other choice, the archetype is still quite small so it really relays on swarming from deck, either way, the three of them are very good cards that almost never represent a brick on hand. 3x/1x Danger! Nessie!/Dogman!: One of the examples of "easy" to summon lv7 monsters, and after some testing, arguably the worst ones, yes they're extenders and give some draw power (la berth combos with them). BUT the random nature of Danger! makes them really unreliable, a wrong discard can be really detrimental and by themselves (no other cards on hand) they're practically useless. The 3/1 ratio obviously goes on favor of Nessie since she's the searcher. 3x Instant Contact/The Ascended of Thunder: Really good extenders and combo pieces, basically free lv7 bodies on board anytime, anywhere, just by giving LP (like, does that even matters in modern YGO?, lmao), the ascended of thunder it's not even OPT. 3/3 is a must. 2x Psi-beast/Astral Kuriboh: A tricky pair. Psi-beast comboes really well with la berth/prepare to extend even further and Astral Kuriboh is a free lv7 that can make a harder to get rid of Diablosis/Harmonizer (remember that this is a lingering effect, so even if their effects get negated they remain indestructible) .The only reason i don't just dump the dangers and play 3 of each is because of "Seven Star Sword", which needs a lv7 monster aaaaand, thinking it again, i may just do that. Needs some testing tho. 3x Ash/Imperm: Nothing to explain here, just the HT's (if you want to swap them for other one go ahead). 1x Pankatrops: Kinda a tech. Is only useful on turn 2 onwards but gives isolation and puts pressure on board, may be drop on an update. 3x Seven Star Sword: A staple on the deck, not only the draw power is really good, it also comboes with ksha by using la berth/prepare to just re-summon the monster you just banished. 2x Pot of Desires/Triple Tactics Talents: Still not convinced with desires, yes, since this list uses 3 of each ksha monster is really unlikely you'd just banish 3 copies of the same one, but i just don't like to risk it, you know?. TTT is basically called by cope, another option would be a handtrap such as veiler/droll. Desires is semi-limited and 3 TTT is an overkill, so i think 2/2 is okay. 3x Kshatri-La Berth: I can see why some people won't run it at 3 like i do, but it's just so useful, to the point where you want to see it in your opening hand, even if the following copies are unusable, it's just great. 1x Kshatri-La Prepare: Useful, but not as useful as La Berth, if by some misfortune i lose it, well, i'll just have to deal with it. Extra Deck: Instant contact targets, various R7NK options to deal with various situations and Soldier of chaos because we are using lv7 monsters. But the most important ones are "Kshatri-La Shangri-La" which gives you the swarming capabilities to out-resource your opponent while also blocking their zones. "Number 89: Diablosis the Mind Hacker", Shangri-La's sidekick, by removing from play cards directly from the Extra Deck you can really block your opponents play, and he's an huge contributor of shangri-la's lockdown. "Number 76 Harmonizer Gradielle" another target for astral kuriboh, a decent way of disrupting plays by attaching opponent's monster from the GY. (Still testing)

Disclaimer: This is NOT how to play Salamangreat! I've been dying to write another Salamangreat decklist in forever. Problem is, there are so many tournament decklists, why bother writing up my own. Not because it's bad or worse but because tournament decks have a level of credibility other decklists don't. So there's no reason for you guys to check out my regular Salamangreat list if you could netdeck one that topped. *insert bragging about being 4-1 at regionals with Salamangreats and then delete this note* I'm not playing some weird tech either that would make it worth discussing over. My Salamangreat list is the most basic it's ever been: Bufferlo, Salamangreats, Heatsoul and Handtraps. I will say I fell in love with Will of the Salamangreats again and put it at 2 after playing it at 1 since forever and I love it and Bufferlo always has and always will be the best card in the game! See, 2 sentences and you've probably figured out my entire decklist by now without even looking at it.  After extensively making clear as to why you don't need a Salamangreat decklists coming from me, here's a Salamangreat decklist :-)))))) SIKE! Well, sike but also not really sike. It's not how I would advise you to play Salamangreat. Earlier I said I didn't play any tech cards, right? So this list is "What If: Salamangreats were teched to the brink?"   The Cyberse Techs We had Dragon Link and then recently Plant Link as link decks that revolve around a type rather than an archetype and while Cyberse has pretty much always been able to, Heatsoul is what started making Cyberse Link a viable choice recently. But what I didn't like about that is how they used Salamangreat as an engine to get into Heatsoul. No Rage. No Roar. So this is the Cyberse Link stuff cramped into a Salamangeat deck. The gameplan is unchanged. Make Sunlight Wolf or Heatsoul but now you can end on either an omni negate that banishes and/or an omni negate, a handloop and monster removal on top of it.
  • Code Talker
    • You're probably familiar with this one. People have tried to cope this into existence for Salamangreat decklists for a while and it never really came about.
    • Micro Coder: You use it in hand to summon a Code Talker monster from the Extra Deck to then search Cynet Conflict.
    • Cynet Conflict: Salamangreat Roar but for Code Talkers.
    • Prior it was used to summon Transcode Talker using Micro Coder and Sunlight Wolf, then summon Wolf again with Transcode and then Reincarnate Summon that Wolf. Now you have an additional omni negate, Wolf and Transcode have more ATK and can't be targeted.
    • Now can be used to make Heatsoul instead. Included some Coder Talker Link-2s to use Micro Coder with.
    • Slightly raises the ceiling but also consumes more ressources and you can't recurse Gazelle with Wolf using the classic Transcode line.
 
  • Mathmech
    • Now we're getting to the good stuff. This one is not even out yet in the TCG but it's a pretty strong 1-card engine over in the OCG (if it doesn't see any play it's because OCG keeps inventing new ways to pull of a tier 0 format)
    • Mathmech Circular: Sends an absolute Sigma Male from your deck the Graveyard to SS itself. If a Mathmech is then summoned it adds a Mathmech S/T.
    • Mathmech Sigma: Chad just summons itself from the freaking graveyard. So cool.
    • Mathmech Superfactorial: The trap you then add with Circular. XYZ summons on your opponent's turn (it's good I promise)
    • Primathmech Alembertian: overlay Circular and Sigma for this one, detach both to add a Mathmech monster to hand and then tribute itself to summon that monster.
    • Mathmech Diameter: A Mathmech Synchro or XYZ using this card as material gets an omni negate effect the turn it is summoned.
    • Link off Diameter to start your play, most often into Balelynx.
    • Primathmech Laplacian: On your opponent's turn use the trap to SS all three monsters and use them to make this XYZ. then you can loop a random card out of your opponent's hand, send a monster he control and out a backrow (this one won't come up often)
    • Now your opponent's is a card short in hand, a monster on the field is gone and you still have an omni negate left. This combo is insane and that's a 1-card combo without using up your normal summon. 
  Is this the best way to play Salamangreat? I doubt it, at least not in this form. But is it funny? Slightly!

deck_description: This is a deck from a previous upload I did. Disclaimer I did not put in the newer card. You can substitute the hand traps with any other hand trap or even pots; (forbidden droplet would probably make this deck better but tbh I haven't bought the card so I didn't "test" it in this deck).  This deck helps you work around almost any deck. how you use it is that using the Invokers as the muscle and the pushup as the engine/"emergency backup" Because you are playing invoker you'll have access to many combinations and safe guards. In this deck your elements (for invoke) will consist of Fire (mainly), earth, and dark. You can use other elements if you want to use hand traps as materials (ogre for example--has come in handy).  The Suship engine uses the Invoker field spell to activates its own effects.  DPE- Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer can be summoned through Invoker's Meltdown. The down side is that you'll have to gather the materials by drawing; which can be covered through the drawing mechanic of Suship and any pot cards you can substitute. deck_name: Shaddoll Deck Trap control 2022 - Post  may banlist
deck_description: Hi! I'm back to post some of my new decks. Stay tune

The ideal opening hand for this deck should be 1x Aluber the Jester of Despia and 1x of any Witchcrafter monster. First thing you do is summon Aluber, activate his effect, add Branded Fusion then activate Branded Fusion and use any Witchcrafter monster + Fallen Of Albaz to fusion summon Albion The Branded Dragon, activate its effect and use the Fallen you just used for Abilion and the Aluber on your field to fusion summon Lubellion the Searing Dragon, after that activate its effect to fusion summon Vice-master by discarding the one Witchcrafter monster in your hand and using it as a material with the other Witchcrafter that you sent to the graveyard by summoning Albion. After getting Vice-Master on the field, you have a non-targetable destruction of one card on the fiel to disrubt your opponent. If you have something like Witchcrafter Creation, use it to add Witchcrafter Golem Aruru for protection and a bounce on one card your opponent controls, if he tries to attack your Vice-Master or try to destroy it. After that your focus should be to get Witchcrafter Madame Verre on the field, so you can have a negate on all your opponents face up monsters that he currently controls by discarding one spell from your hand which you can immediately add back by using Vice-Master's effect. If your fusion summons are disrubted, try and summon 2 of your level 8 monster on your turn so you can at least go into Number 38 to have some protection. If the dragons that you used to get Vice-Master on the field are still alive on your next turn you can go into Dingirsu or Number 38 depending on the situation. You cna also use Vice-Master to try and destroy Dingirsu with her destruction, then send one of the materials to the graveyard and if it's Albion, during the end phase add one Branded Fusion or Branded Opening depending on if you have a DARK monster to use for 2 other dragons. Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon is just a backup if you can't go into Vice-Master as it can send something like Ash or Abyss Dragon to the graveyard to add more Branded cards in the end phase and non-target banish one monster on the field. Getting the lower level Witchcrafters will be easy for you with Vice-Master's effect and with them you can special summon one of the higher levels Witchcrafters by discarding one spell but with Vice-Master's third effect you essentially do this for no cost, as you can add back the spell card you just discarded. If by any chance your opponent tries to destroy your fusion monsters by a card effect, you can just banish Branded Fusion and protect them This is my first time making something like this, i hope you enjoy the deck!

deck_excerpt: An exerpimental and much cheaper idea for Solfachords that does not just end on Avramax pass
deck_description: OVERVIEW  Solfadark is a combination of the solfachord main deck monsters and a dark engine that consists of Armageddon Knight, Zephyros, The PK engine, Destiny Hero Malicious, and the very well known Darkwurm + Dragon Shrine + Gate setup that so many Solfachord decks use. The main idea of the deck is that your gameplay is setup into two separate parts: before pendulum summoning and after pendulum summoning.  The solfachord engine works amazingly to setup for a card like Beyond The Pendulum, which can then search for a missing pendulum scale (usually gate), harmonizer magician as it leads to halq very easily and special summons more material, or Gracia so you can get your field spell out. After your pendulum summon you will mainly be relying on your dark engine pieces (mainly the phantom knight cards unless you draw into Arma) to generate resources because a large majority of the time you will be able to link Beyond The Pendulum and another dark monster such as a plague spreader or darkwurm in order to go into rusty bardiche. From that point you can send cloak, set the brigandine, banish the cloak to add boots, and get creative with the raw amount of materials you can now put on the field. This concept was developed after realizing the deck does not need cards like Loagaeth as they can already get the materials on board for BTP fairly consistently, but struggle to find more resources after pendulum summoning. Cards like Diviner of The Herald are still AMAZING in Solfachord, the only problem is that I am not an oil baron who can drop $240 on a playset of them compared to this much cheaper and equally as effective alternative. Despite being a 45 card deck I have found that its incredibly consistent and also can not think of any cards to take out, if you have any ideas of cards to take out or some ideas on how to improve the deck please shoot me a message on twitter @Gliscare.     Basic Combo: Assuming a two card hand of Cutia + Dragon Shrine you can go into the following: Dragon Shrine Send Darkwurm, special darkwurm, add Gate Zero Normal Cutia, add Dreamia Darkwurm + Cutia make BTP, set  Gate and Dreamia as scales Add harmonizer to hand Pendulum Summon Cutia, Darkwurm, and Harmonizer. Activate Harmonizer to special summon Oafdragon BTP + Darkwurm to make Rusty Bardiche, Bardiche send cloak, set Brigandine and special summon it, banish cloak add Boots and special summon Boots Harmonizer + Cutia, Boots, or Brigandine to make Halq, special summon plague spreader Plague Spreader + Oafdragon make Borrelload Savage Dragon, target BTP in grave From here you can either make a three material Apollousa or use the leftover materials to make IP, then use IP + Halq to make Avramax which can be very hard to out if your opponent is not ready for it. Banish boots and set fog blade  In addition to that combo theres also a number of extensions you can do via Armageddon Knight by sending cards like Zephyros to the grave so you can summon a hand trap off of halq and then bounce it back to your hand with Zephyros or by sending Malicious to grave for extra material. Whatever you do the deck is shockingly versatile and is an absolute blast to play once you start looking into it more and more. The deck can play through a negate or two depending on the hand, though as it is still solfachords it is painfully fragile at times hence why cards like Instant Fusion and Called By The Grave are here.  "Why is Instant Fusion Here" Instant Fusion is always an amazing card to draw as it can summon Restrict to protect your Cutia, BTP, or Armageddon Knight from being negated or you can summon Ciel to have a pendulum for BTP in a pinch (it comes up alot more than you'd think). Ciel is an espescially good target as you can pendulum summon her back to the field like any other face up pendulum monster so she can recur herself if you have the proper scales.

My pretty budget way to play Unchained  You can use unchained monsters passively (set one of the lower unchained monsters and let them spawn each other in the turn of the enemy) or aggressively ( attack the enemy multiple times. By using the quick effect of Rakea or Escape of the unchained you can destroy your monsters during Battle Phase for extra dmg).  After some iterations (also playing this deck as Evil Eye + Unchained), I can say this deck has reached a fairly balanced state. Going first or 2nd is completely valid.  Going first I try to end on I:P, Soul of Rage and Rakea. This allows me to activate the effect of I:P and chain Soul of Rage as CL2 right after a monster has been summoned by the opponent. Linking into a link 3 with a monster of the enemy and link into a link 4 (unchained abomination or avramax) with I:P. Rakea could now trigger abominations effect.  Elsewise the deck is built so that enemy bord destruction is allways possible.  Side deck is almost only for playing against backrow heavy decks.

deck_excerpt: A deck that is overdue of revitalization by gutting out the rotting meat, only by simply getting rid of a single rotting carcass.
deck_description: Video link is in the description below -Exo ( https://youtu.be/V1ORCdoUKso )   So there isn't much to be discussed today for I have other plans in real life. I was bored and decided to spend more time practicing on utilizing obscure and absurd tech options with rogue decks. That being said, today's deck is basically a can of Whoop-Ass; but that said can has maggots, cockroaches, and possibly mosquitos infected with malaria virus. To fix this, I disposed the said can of Whoop-Ass, and replaced it with a fresh can of actual fresh tasting utilities and flavor. Now we must proceed to the usual descriptions of what it is that said current thing of thing, because it is my job to do so.   First and foremost, Geomathmech Final Sigma is no more; but if you can't make proper link plays and have Mystic Mine ready to be played, then you can go for pass for your opponents turn. Now besides what I mentioned earlier, one in particular I have been working on utilizing for Mathmechs is the newly released Link-3 monster, Decode Talker Heatsoul: a link monster that has a quick effect that draws 1 card for 1000LP (during either players turn); and can Special summon a Link-3 or lower Cyberse monster from your Extra deck (if your LP's are 2000 or lower) by banishing the card from the field. Now, I have also used the Mystic Mine pass with Decode Talker Heatsoul, and I prefer it over Geomathmech Final Sigma for reasons of consistency over OTK utilization. Plus given I can have proper target for Transcode Talker given I have used most of my Link monsters for Accesscode Talker.   Next comes the other stuff I have worked with that I never expected to use; but used anyways for better or worse. Despite the banning of Predaplant Verte Anaconda, Artifact Scythe can still be utilized in two different ways: either with Crystron Halqifibrax to T.G. Wonder Magician (which was the most easiest and common way of activating the Scythe Lock); or a Link-2 monster within the Artifact archetype known as Artifact Dagda (which can set it during either players turn when an effect is played; but is destroyed during the end phase, which makes it more predictable). Then comes the newly limited card Change of Heart (which allows you to control a monster until the End Phase, regardless of what type of monster it is). Honorable mentions in my deck include Flame Bufferlo (which is a +2, -1 if removed from the field), Primathmech Alembertian (an XYZ monster that just searches for Mathmech pieces such as "Mathmech Diameter"), and Parallel eXceed (special summons itself from the hand if you link summon during your turn, then special summons another copy of itself from your deck; but both copies are treated as LV4).

deck_excerpt: A control build of Salamangreats that recycle their spells and traps to clear the field and disrupt opponents' plays
deck_description: This is a fun, control style deck build of Salamangreats that I have been play testing with. You use Salamangreat Sunlight Wolf to recycle your Salamangreat spells and traps (Most Notably Salamangreat Roar), and you utilize those spells and traps to keep your opponent from building an unbreakable board. You will also utilize the effect of Salamangreat Heatleo to shuffle opponents' spells and traps back into the deck, helping to clear the way for Salamangreat Pyro Phoenix.  You will end on Salamangreat Pyro Phoenix to clear any remaining obstacles that your opponent my have left on their board.

Going first, try to get Flare Metal out ASAP, going second, you can go for anything, but I would suggest Archfiend Black Skull Dragon, since your opponents can't activate effects if it attacks. If you have any suggestions, message me on Discord, my user is Ace_Sqweeks#6745. Please don't flood my messages with rude comments, tho...

While looking at old Yugioh cards I came across the "gagagigo" cards and thought that I should make a deck themed around gagagigo and similar looking lizardman-looking cards. So after hours of searching through different archetypes trying to find cards that I believe roughly resemble the gagagigo/lizardman look I ended up with this, The Lizardman Aliens deck. The engine of this deck is the Alien archetype engine, unfortunately unlike my other decks this one didn't meld together as well but it's still a functioning deck although pretty slow sometimes depending on your hand. If you're a fan of casual slower games this deck is good for you however against pretty much any other casual deck you'll probably get stomped.  The point of the decks I am making is to take a theme I like and make a cool deck with it and as long as the deck functions properly and is cool then I'll post it.  Anyway, thanks for checking out this weird Lizardman-Alien deck!

deck_excerpt: AdventureDragonLink (TCG) JUNE 2022  -I've worked a lot with Dragon Link and this is the current version I run.
deck_description: The basic idea of the deck is using the brave engine and red rose engine to create card advantage and to use the dragon link engine as powerful extenders to end on power-houses such as Baronne De Fleur, Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss (Hot Red),  the recently released Borrelend Dragon, I:P and Borreload Savage Dragon. Often times you also put a Fairy Tail Snow in the grave to have more points of interruption. The deck uses its crazy amounts of extension and high potential boards to completely shut out an opponent going first and to push through interruptions going second.  The most basic combo of the deck only needs Rite of Aramesia and any Tuner monster in the deck. The standard combo of the deck needs Rite of Aramesia, Any Normal Summon, and any Extender. Dragon Link has many powerful extenders like Chaos Space & Quick Launch. Both cards create loads of card advantage (Both are normally a plus 2-5 in card advantage) and allow you to extend into more plays. The deck is very consistent. With my testing, the deck has a 9/10 for playable hands with 7/10 being full combo (low on bricks) and an average 1 hand-trap/going-second card per hand. One weakness of the deck is a lack of going second card room, this is why I main Forbidden Droplet, for its high impact in the current meta going second. The last cards I want to mention are Chaos Dragon Levianeer & Chaos Ruler The Chaotic Magical Dragon. Due to the deck's playstyle, it is not as consistent to get Levi into rotation but it is still viable as an extra option for massively powerful effects such as Non-Targerting Destruction x2 & Hand Ripping, both effects a plus 2 in card advantage and very impactful. Chaos Ruler is the gambler of the deck. He enables a powerful boss monster in Hot Red and gives you the potential for massive amounts of advantage in sending 4 cards into your grave and 1 to your hand (Normally Effect Veiler or a Levi). I don't think it's an unpopular opinion that Dragon link is very hard to pilot, and while I do think that the use of the adventure engine makes the deck easier to play I don't think that the higher ceiling of difficulty is gone. Because at the core the dragon link cards are the cards that win you games. Borrelend Dragon is the new MVP of the deck and frankly, a lot of decks don't have consistent ways to out the card making it a real obstacle for some players. Thank you for reading and I hope you try out the deck :) DB- BumpyBlue
