deck_excerpt: October 2022 Gizmek deck with a P.U.N.K engine and Telefon combo the can end in 3 link-4 and a Zeus.
deck_description:
Note* this text is has been entirely rewritten as of The October 2022 banlist, and the decklist updated after the ban of Halquifibrax. This version is a more of a place holder while I experiment with exact ratios. This may be updated again in the near future.

 

In this re-write I'll be going over the new combos, how this deck fairs against the meta and how to overcome it, and cards to swap in if the deck isn't quite working for you. For those re-reading this, I'll cut to the chase and start off with the new stuff so you don't have to re-read everything:

 

Ancient Gear Ballista-

This card is the predecessor of Crystron halquifibrax for this deck. It's a link 2 that takes 2 earth machines, on link summon, It adds Ancient gear from your deck to your hand. Ancient gear can special summon itself, or be used as a Discard for Knightmare Unicorn during a Telefon loop. Furthermore, Ancient Gear Ballista can pop Clockwork Night to give you Clockwork night's search effect and make an opponent's monsters ATK drop to 0 to help with OTKs. That's the card's use on it's own, but there are combo's for it, though I haven't discovered it's full potential as I only thought of using it last night. Alongside Urgent Schedule, this card takes you from brick to a minimoun of a Link-2 and 3 bodies on board and can tie into P.U.N.K combos if your opponent has an earth monster. So start off by summoning Gizmek Tainguku and Gizmek Uka with Urgent Schedule. Use both as link material for Ancient Gear Ballista, and use Ballista's effect to add and special summon Ancient Gear. Then banish Gizmek Tainguku to special summon Gizmek Uka from your gy, this triggers Uka's effect to special summon a monster from the deck. And the combo you go into from there vaties on what's in your hand and what you were able to summon from the deck. It can get as good as I:P Avramax + Hope Harbinger + Zeus off of just Urgent Schedule alone. This combo and the Garunteed discard for Knightmare Unicorn are all I've discovered for it so far though.

 

New Telefon Looping Methods-

Sadly Halquifibrax got banned, but, there were enough ways to get Telefon on the field that Machine Duplication could pick up the slack. Telefon looping is done by having a Telefon on the field, and one in the gy. Telefon can summon Telefon from the gy, then use the Telefon that did that as material, then the newly summoned Telefon can summon the other Telefon back from the gy, causing an infinite summon loop that lets you gain LP in the process. So the first method is to-

  1. Summon a Single Telefon(Normal summon/Gizmek Naganaki effect/Urgent Schedule effect/Gizmek Tainguku effect/Gizmek Uka uka effect/Small world then normal summon).
  2. Activate Machine Duplication, this summons 2 more Telefon to your field.
  3. Use 2 Telefon to link summon Ancient Gear Ballista, and activate it's effect to add Ancient gear to your hand. Then loop both back.
  4. Use 2 Telefon to link summon I:P Masquerena. Use Ballista And Masquerena to Link summon Mekk Knight Crusadia Avramax. And loop both back.
  5. Use 2 Telefon to Link summon Qliphort Genius. Loop both back, then, use Genius to negate one and a card your opponent controls. Then use the negated telefon and Genius to link summon Knightmare unicorn.
  6. Use Unicorns effect to discard Ancient Gear to shuffle a card your opponent controls back into the deck. Then use it and a Telefon to link summon Accesscode Talker. 
  7. Loop 1 Telefon back in DEFENSE POSITION, this Telefon will let you look at up to the top 6 cards of your deck depending on the dice roll, and organize them however you like, and if you don't like them, Telefon lets you put the cards on the bottom of your deck. Use both remaining Telefon to xyz summon Assembled Nightingale. After the battle phase, Nightingale can be used as xyz material to summon Zeus.

Depending on what else you could get on the board, it's possible to make a combo consisting of up to 3 of 4 negate Apollousa, 3 negate Borreload Savage Dragon, Barrone de fleur, Hope Harbinger, Therion King, and Chengying in addition to the 5k Accescode & I:P Avramax & Zeus that the Telefon loop gave you.

The second Loop is a lot harder. You need to get 3 Telefon on the field/gy using any number of these different methods, before repeating the previous loop into your 2 link-4s and Zeus. You can use-

  • Normal summon Gizmek Naganaki, then special summon Gizmek Arakami with its own effect. Tribute Arakami using Naganaki's effect to special summon Telefon from the deck. The banish Arakami using its own effect to send a Telefon from the deck to the gy.
  • Using just Naganaki or Arakami.
  • Sending Telefon from the hand to the gy via Foxy Tune or Clockwork Night effect.
  • Normal summon a Telefon.
  • Use urgent Schedule to special summon a Telefon from the deck.
  • Activate Gizmek Ukas effect that special summons Telefon/Gizmek Naganaki from the deck.

And loop once you have the three Telefon. In the instance you draw a bunch of cards you can special summon via their own effects, it's possible to Telefon loop using just 2 Telefon.

 

Other new stuff-

Ash blossom and Infinite Impermanence were added for disruption in place of a few cards you'll notice missing such as the field spells. With all the new cards that didn't have balanced stats, and and the 3 more spells, Gizmek Scrolls become less consistent. Therion discollusseum wasn't drawn enough to be a keeper over my other options to take out, so Terraforming followed suit. I took out the Chimeratech board wipe for being inconsistent, and I took out a Foxy Tune since you only need to search it once. Silent Grave Yard was added to the side deck to help against Tearalaments, and Ojama Trio was added to fend off Mystic mine(gives your opponent 3 monsters so you can mak unicorn to shuffle Mystic Mine back into the deck.)

 

Qliphort Genius combos-

Back to old stuff again, however Ancient Gear Ballista does spice up this old combo. Qliphort genius is a Link-2 that can negate a monster's effect you control other than itself to negat a face up card your opponent controls. It's unaffected by spells and traps so if it was out before skill drain was activated, it can negate it for the turn. In adition to that, it has another effect that let's you add a level 5 or higher machine from your deck to your hand if 2 monsters are summoned at the same to the zones it points to. The old play was to summon 2 machines(Arakami/Naganaki/Orochi/Uka/Therion King), then link them off for Genius. Then activate Urgent Schedule summoning 2 machines, then activate Genius effect to add Gizmek kaku. Banish Arakami you used for Genius to send Gizmek Orochi from your deck to the gy. Now you have a link-2 and 2-4 bodies that can easily be used to synchro spam. In this combo you can do things like small world a Gizmek Naganaki/Arakami/Uka to your hand, and banish Naganaki from the gy to get yet another body on board.

But, this combo is now twice as consistent, and twice as powerful. It goes like this-

  1. Summon 2 machines for Qliphort Genius. Now, use either Urgent Schedule or Machine Duplication to summon 2 Earth machines to the arrows, allowing you to add Uka/Orochi/Kaku/Therion king regulus from your deck to your hand.
  2. Use both monsters Genius points to to Link summon Ancient Gear Ballista, and add Ancient gear from your deck to your hand and special summon it. You can use cards like Tainguku to summon uka from your gy and give you another two bodies, and you allready have two bodies in your hand you can summon from your hand via their own effects. You can use things like Emergency teleport or Ukas effect to atart P.U.N.K comboing in addition, if you used Machine Duplication, you can start Telefon looping in addition. This combo pretty much has it all. Without Telefon you can still end up with 2 link 2 and up to 7 bodies for comboing. 

On it's own, this card negates hinderinces and let you combo under cards such as Skill drain, Gozen match, and Zombie world.

 

P.U.N.K Combos-

PUNK help get cards to the gy for their gy effects, and can make a 1 card combo into a Zeus, or when in a combo, Can make Hope Harbinger and Zeus/Baronne:

  1. Normal summon Ze Amin or special summon it off of Gizmek Uka/Emergency Teleport.
  2. Activate it's effect to add Foxy Tune. 
  3. Activate Foxy tunes effect to discard a card to summon Deer note(the discard can allow for effects like that of Clockwork Night or Gizmek Tainguku, and the summon can trigger Gizmek Uka,).
  4. Use Deer note and Ze Amin to synchro summon JAM Dragon Drive. Then either;

Use Deer note to revive Ze Amin, and use JAM to add and summon Psychic Wheeleder. Use both level 3s to xyz summon JaJa, and make Zeus after the battle phase.

Revive Foxy tune and if you add it to the deck, add Ghost Ogre to your hand, then use both level 8 to xyz summon Hope Harbinger.

 

Kaiju & co.-

Kaijus, Nibiru, Lava Golem, and Sphere mode are all famous for their role of tributing opponents monsters before they can react, easily wipung threats away like a speck of dust on the play mat. Sphere mode is the best of these cards for the current format, however this deck uses Kumongus the sticky string kaiju. Kaijus have different attributes, and allow you to control what you summon off of Gizmek Uka. Kumongus lets you summin cards like Telefon and Ze Amin off of uka. Where as all Spheres can get you is a self destructing Obelisk the Tormentor. So I prefer Kaijus, but it's up to your preference here. 3 monsters, or 1 monster and a combo. The different Kaijus have different summons you can gain off of them, for every kaiju, there is a Gizmek card that shares the attribute, excluding WIND. So any can be used. Being a level 7, if you manage to get a Kaiju to your field you can easily use it as Baronne material.

 

Clockwork Night-

This card has a few uses, the first one being an OTK. Urgent Schedule lets you go into some insane combos, but, only machines can attack the turn you use it. The majority of your extra deck aren't machines. But, Clockwork night not only makes them machines, but gives them 500 extra ATK while making your opponent loose 500. This let's you attack over pretty much anything. The second use is it's search effect. After being sent to the gy via foxy tune/knightmare unicorn/ancient gear ballista, you can banish it to discard a card, and search an earth machine. Letting you gain gy effects of your Gizmeks and letting you add powerful cards like Therion King Regulus.

 

Cards to swap in-

1×Ghost Ogre: Ghost ogre can be searched by Dragon Drive.

1xMachina Citadel: a good main deck boss monster if you can get it to the gy, it can destroy itself to destroy all monsters with less that 3000ATK on the field, and whenever an earth machine you control is destroyed, it summons itself back to the field.

3× Cyber Dragon nachester/1×Chimeratech Fortress dragon: ockwork night makes all monsters machine, so if you have nachester on your field, you can use it and all of your opponents monsters as fusion material for chimeratech fortress dragon. However you can't search clockwork night so this was rather inconsistent and removed from the deck.

1×Scarlight red dragon archfiend: Scarlight can destroy all monsters with lower or equal ATK to it. Alongside Clockwork night, this card can wipe away a card that was once at 4000ATK,  with Chengying, you can wipe away practically anything if enough cards are banished. Even better, Scarlight deals 500 damage for each card destroyed, dealing up to 5500 effect damage and 3000 battle damage all on its own in a full field.

Gizmek Inaba, the hopping hare of hakuto: More OTK stuff, you can banish this card from the gy to make a face up machine you control whos stats are balanced gain ATK equal to that of all other machines you control with balanced stats, but only it can attack this turn. Ancient gear balista can change an opponents ATK to 0, so in a Qliphort Genius combo, it's possible to give a single gizmek enough ATK to OTK.

Limiter removal: This card doubles all your machines ATK, but destroys them during the end phase. So another OTK card. Clockwork night makes Avramax a machine with 3500ATK, that gets doubled to 7000! 7500 if you count the fact that Clockwork night makes your opponent's monster loose 500ATK. Due to Avramax's effect, it will almost alwayse deal it's ATK stat as damage, meaning on its own this card will almost alwayse do 7500 damage in this scenario. Accesscode talker's ATK can shoot up as high as 11600!

Gizmek Scrolls: This field spell lets you look at the top 3 cards of your deck to add a machine with balanced stats to your hand,  and banish the other two face down. It has an additional effect to where when you summon a monster with balanced stats 10 times, all monsters wothout balanced stats have their effects negated. This excludes link monsters.

Therion discollusseum: this field spell lets you add a Therion King regulus to your hand upon activation. It also gives you battle protection once per turn that lets you add another therion king regulus.

Brain research lab: normal summon P.U.N.K in addition to your normal summon/set.

Terraforming.

Iron call: monster reborn for level 4 and lower machines but their effects are negated.

Dimensional  barrier: pick an extra deck mechanic, it doesn't exist this turn.

 

Meta/Bad matchups & how to counter it-

Spright- pretty much lost their spark now but you still see them around. Use a negate on spright Blue/starter, silent graveyard stops frog shinanigans, and most of the time you should be able to combo around 2 or 3 negates.

Branded- you can outlast branded resource wise, if you need to, they honestly don't do alot other than banish a single card and change your ATK to zero, the occasional shrimp that can attack all your monsters. Other than that it's play around generic disruption as you usually would.

Exosister- step 1. Pray. Step 2. Kaiju. Exosister suck, this deck relies on it's gy alot so really you need a kaiju, or bait them while trying to make zeus so you can combo next turn when you get your gy back.

Tearalaments- The second threat, you have Silent gy to shut them entirely down if you draw it, you have your 7 disruption cards, your kaijus who don't help much as it triggers fusion summoning. Ojama trio helps too funnily enough, they only get 2 monster zones and an extra monster zone that way, which cuts how much they can fusion summon against you. If you manage to get a barrier statue out alongside Avramax, you can kill them as they won't be able to summon at all. So go first and pray for a decent hand.

Trap based decks- Just use red reboot. Oh wait, konami decided right now was a great time to ban it and give them a card that searches normal traps right after giving them a monster that searches continuous traps. You can use Cosmic cyclone to banish the troublesome ones, Ojama trio saves the day again as it stops eldilich from harassing you with trap monsters. Making therion king early in a turn can help a TON, but other than that you play like usual. Against cards like there can be only one and gozen match, Qliphort genius can negate them. In rare cases, you can make Genius under summon limit. Knightmare unicorn and I:P Masquerena are both different types from eachother and your machine based deck, allowing you to make unicorn under there can be only one to shuffle it back into the deck.

Mystic mine- banish it with cosmic space cyclone. Ojama trio can give your opponent 3 monsters, allowing you to compress your board into a knightmare unicorn so you can shuffle the mystic mine away, then set up negates to stop it from coming back out.

Zombie world & co.- these cards change your typing from machine, wrecking your plays. Knightmare unicorn, cosmic space cyclone, qliphort genius, and clockwork night negate these kind of cards. 

Kshatri-la- I haven't fought them, but they are going to be meta with that new support no doubt. Firstly, Gizmek has a strange archtype specific damage control. Kshatri la banish your cards face down, but Gizmek Naganaki can add a face down banished machine with balanced stats from banished face down to your hand. So that helps. This archtype has a variety of attributes, so barrier statue Avramax hits them hard. They are a somewhat combo deck so Ojama trio should help by filling monster zones, but you are a combo deck as well, so them negating your ability to use zones is just as impactful.

 

That's all for now, as always, hope you enjoy!

deck_excerpt: Imagine Making a Retrain of an Archetype, and Completely Removing It's Characteristic Mechanic...
deck_description: Armed Dragon is an archetype of Wind Dragon Level monsters introduced in GX, and like most things introduced in the GX era of the TCG, it wasn't very good. However, they have recently gotten a retrain series called Armed Dragon Thunder, which entirely remove the mechanic of them Leveling Up after certain conditions have been met, and are instead able to send a monster from your hand and that card to the GY to special summon an Armed Dragon monster of the step up or anything beneath(i.e. LV5 can summon LV7 or below).  For the decklist, we have an Armed Dragon package of 1x Thunder LV10, 1x LV10 White, 2x Pile Armed, 3x Thunder LV7, 3x Thunder LV5, 3x Thunder LV3, 3x Flash, 2x Lightning, for the rest of the Main Deck, we have a Handtrap lineup of 3x Ash Blossom, 3x Maxx C, 2x D.D. Crow, and 2x Veiler, 1x Apex Avian, 1x Tempest Dragon Ruler of Storms, 3x Bombarding Catapult Turtle, 1x Barrier Statue of the Stormwinds, 1x Dragon Buster Destruction Sword, 3x Pot of Prosperity, and 2x Called By, for the Extra Deck, we have 1x Zeus, 1x Liebe, 1x Gustav Max, 1x Galaxy Tomohawk(because it isn't banned in the OCG or Master Duel for some reason), 1x Underworld Goddess, 1x Accesscode, 2x Simorgh Link, 1x Knightmare Unicorn, 1x Knightmare Phoenix, 1x Harpie Conductor, 1x Union Carrier, 1x Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres, 1x Link Spider, and 1x Imduk.

deck_excerpt: Banish is the name of the game. Banish everything, swing with Gren Maju.
deck_description: BANISH, BANISH, BANISH! The entire point of this deck is to banish as many card as possible in order to boost Gren Maju's attack. You can use Gizmek Orochi to special summon itself by banishing the top 8 cards of you deck, face-down in order to summon it. You will want to use Gold Sarcophagus to banish Necroface, which will banish the top 5 cards of both players' decks if it is banished. You can use Eater of Millions to deal with troublesome boss monsters, then tag it out with Masked Hero Dark Law for extra damage, as well as a one-sided Macro Cosmos. You want to use Stall Turn to negate your opponents' negates, on a counter trap that banishes the top 3 cards of your deck, face-down for activation cost. If you feel like you are running low on cards, you can normal summon Necroface, which will shuffle all banished cards back into their owners' deck, and gain 100 attack for each.

deck_excerpt: A Fish Synchro/Xyz toolbox combo deck. Very powerful in a casual format
deck_description:
White Aura Fish Synchro Combos: This is a fish Synchro/Xyz spam combo deck that takes advantage of some of the insane generic water and fish support. It can do some crazy things facilitate floodgates, OTKs, and play through some disruptions. It can take advantage of a very large Sychro and Rank 4 Xyz pool. This mostly operates at a casual to low-rouge status. It won’t take any event tops, but could definitely steal some wins.   This deck has a few combo/playlines that come up fairly frequently. The main goal is to spit out your giant boss monsters from the depths. If you are going first try and make Adamancipator Dragite, for the disruption and if your going second try and make White Aura Whale and Bihamut for a potential OTK. This deck can take advantage and make almost any synchro monster, using Magalancia you can alter the monster levels to make any synchro needed. This deck can also utilize some of the new support from the Duelist from the Deep Booster. This is probably one of my favorite decks ever, I love the idea of all of these ancient and powerful sea monsters rising up from the depths. It s a sold deck and can hold its own quite well in a more casual format.   Combos and Tips:
  1. Your main starters are Lifeless Leafish or Beatunaful Princess to SS Lealfish or Royal Swamp Eel from the deck. Use Leafishe’s foolish burial effect to dump usually Fishborg Launcher or Coelacanth any level 4 fish if you open White Mirror.
  2. The main tuners are Gluttonous Reptolphin Greethys, FIshborg Launcher, and Royal Swamp Eel. You will usually SS Swamp Eel from the deck or the GY. Greethys can SS a fish from the grave and gives his Synchro’d monster a nice attack boost, fishborg you want Foolished for his SS effect.
  3. White Mirror is an insane extender, it’s a +1. The main targets are Silent Angler or Greethys you can SS one from the grave to add the other to the hand you can then SS Silent Angler from the hand for 2 bodies on the field for any Xyz play.
  Main Combos:  
  1. Opening Hand: Greethys + Silent Angler- summon Greethys and SS Angler from the hand. Synchro for White Aura Monoceros, trigger his effect SS Greethys from GY. Use Greethys effect to SS Silent angler back from GY in def. Synchro Greehtys and Monoceros into Barrone de Fleur. Use Greethys effect to boost Fleurs attack to 4000.
  2. Superancient Deepsea King Coelacanth: SS him from GY with Monster Reborn, White Aura Monoceros, Number 37, or Whitefish Salvage. Resolve his effect and SS from the deck Fishborg Launcher, Greethys, Friller Rabica, and any other lvl 4 non tuner. Use FIshborg and the Deepsea King to make Dragite or White Aura Whale, then Greethys and Rabica to make Coral Dragon to then Synchro with the lvl 4 into either White Aura Behaumut or Barrone de Fleur.

With this, your opponents side is soft locked and they will have to spend resources to get rid of your field or end their turn if they are heavily relying on activated effects from monsters.  Still playing around with the build and changing it as I go.

deck_excerpt: Very consistent (and cheap) pure Gravekeeper deck
deck_description: Overview This deck focusses on turboing Supernaturalist (SN) + Necrovalley on to the field as this blocks the opponent from properly accessing their GY (bye Eldlich!) and gives both cards protection from destruction (they still can be banished or returned to the hand). I tuned the deck to be as consistent and as pure as possible, the classical "floodgate gravekeeper" uses too many handtraps, solemns etc. to be consistent (but it can actually work very well, see the side deck for some cards you might want to side in if a more floodgatey playstyle is needed). So lets look at the cards... Necrovalley (+ Terraforming, + Commandant, + Throne) The backbone of the whole archetype. Blocks cards in the GY from being banished, blocks any effect that would move a card from the GY to a different spot (e.g. Monster Reborn) and effects that would include changing types or attributes in the GY (e.g. Zombie Worlds first effect). This card is able to block a lot of plays and we need it to use the effect of Spiritualist for fusion summoning Supernaturalist (and then profiting from the destruction protection). Together with Terraforming and Commandant we practically play 7 versions of necrovalley and because we can search commandant with Throne we basically play 10 copies of necrovalley. Necrovalley also gives all Gravekeeper Monsters a 500 ATK/DEF bonus which makes them quite impressive beatsticks. Spiritualist (+ Polyermerization) The second most important part of our strategy. To fusion summon Supernaturalist (SN) we either need Spiritualist + Necrovalley (see Necrovalley) or we can directly use Polyermization. Personally I found only few builds that use the classical Polymerization but I found it to essential to increase the consistency and amount of options. Supernaturalist Our fusion summoned boss monster. Gains 100 ATK/DEF for each level used for the fusion summoning. Summoning with 2 lv 4s and Necrovalley on the field this already becomes a 3300 ATK and DEF beatstick. Protects itself and Necrovalley from destruction (as long as Necrovalley is on the field). Also gives the opportunity to search a 'Gravekeeper' monster or 'Necrovalley' card from the deck in the end phase (sadly the end phase, that could bring some really strong negates otherwise). You basically have 1 main go-to options here: search for Throne (most generic and strongest search card in the archetype). But you could also search for Hidden Temples or Tomb of Necrovalley as this either gives the option to completely lock out the opponent from special summoning monsters or gives you another negate - but the consistency might be weakened if your opponent is able to break 'your board'. Another option is to search for Headman if you have Spiritualist in the GY: this allows you to special summon her to the field and fusion summon another Supernaturalist. Necrovalley Throne (+ Allure of Darkness, + Upstart Goblin, + Pot of Desires, + Stele) Throne basically lets you search any Gravekeeper monster, in most cases you are either searching Spiritualist or Commandant (the latter to get access to Necrovalley). The second effect is in my experience rarely the right choice, but the side deck contains some Rank 3 and Rank 4 xyz that might be an out in some situations. We also play Allure, Upstart and Desires just to boost our consistency. These cards are essential to get to the cards we want and really need. Also we dont play Demise because we want to turbo out Supernaturalist. Beyond that, Gravekeeper's Stele allows us to add 2 Gravekeeper monsters to our hand from the GY (ignoring Necrovalley) and is together with Headman our only way to recycle ressources. Other Gravekeepers Spy is a strong card with a lot of defense especially if necrovalley is on the field, we can summon Spirtiualist (if there are not attacks left) or Recruiter (for another search if destroyed). Guard is basically only here so we can use non-destruction removal if needed and Descendant if we really need to get rid of a card. Headman can be used to special summon a lvl 4 monster from the GY (sadly Headman is lv 3 otherwise this would be really good opportunity for an xyz summon), main play here is to ressurrect Spirutualist and fusion summon again. In general the ration of Descendant, Recruiter and Guard  doesnt matter too much, they can be tech cards, but mainly we need some monsters for fusion summoning. Sadly I was not really able to get other Gravekeepers cards in here really, most of them are sadly just too bad. Tech Cards (+ Extra Deck) We play the Dark Kaiju Radian (to allow usage of  Allure) and a copy of Rite of Spirit which might help to recover a destroyed Supernaturalist or to further stall the opponent. We play a Starving Venom if we have poly + Kaiju + 1 Dark in our hand, just so we are not stuck doing nothing. The other extra deck cards are just some generic rank3/rank4s  that might come up handy, a really nice tech card is Akashic magician that gives a really nice option for non-destruction removal.

deck_excerpt: Abusing Expressroid + Ambulanceroid to end on a bunch of negates and link monsters
deck_description: A lot of vehicroid decks lean into fusions, as they have a really decent fusion spell in Vehicroid Connection Zone. The fusions themselves are not incredibly impressive, though with the help of Instant/Ready Fusion, Mobile Base should be easy to get out.  However, while the deck CAN do fusions, it mostly specializes in searching for Expressroid and Ambulanceroid to swam the field with roid monsters and get cool link plays. Dragonroid, Gear Gigant X, Pot of Prosperity and Megaroid City help you find them, while the Gadgets get you started, and Platinum is usually how you'll end up getting Expressroid onto the field for its effect.  Emergeroid Call is tempting as an omni-negate, but it's also just another card that returns a roid from grave to hand, which in this case means Special Summon if you have Ambulanceroid out.  Still trying to get the deck as consistent as possible, and while it can't really fit handtraps with this mix of fusion and link summoning, you can theoretically make a much more skim list with only the link aspects and actually have hand traps for interruptions.

deck_name: TikTok Format Tournament Winner: Trickstar Shaddoll
deck_description: Before getting into the rules let me just say this format is not meant to go "try hard" and build the most optimal competitive deck to face off against your opponent. The idea of this format is to keep it casual and run those "bad" Knights of Atlantis, Chazz (Ojama/Armed Dragon/VWXYZ), God Cards and many other casual decks. Basically approach this format as if you're playing on the playground and not at a local game shop for a tournament.  This format was also designed to be used with the Duel Disk toys licensed by Konami. YOU DO NOT NEED A DUEL DISK TO PLAY THIS FORMAT.  Due to this format being made with the Duel Disks in mind there are rules in line limiting certain cards that can't be used with a Duel Disk.  1-Other than the following rules, all other official TCG rules apply.  2-Due to this being made for a Duel Disk XYZ, PENDULUMS, and LINK MONSTERS ARE BANNED!  3- All cards are limited to 1 copy per deck EXCEPT for cards on this list, you can play 3 of anything on this list: https://tinyurl.com/AnimeFormatExceptions  4) Other than Xyz, Pendelum and Links no other cards are banned, but to balance Gameplay there is a <#907791420469956678> You can only have 3 Cards on the A Tier List 5 Cards on the B Tier List 10 Cards on the C Tier List In your deck. https://tinyurl.com/FormatTierList  5)You can Normal Summon in face up defense like the Anime.  6) You can have up to 20 cards in the Extra Deck. deck_excerpt: "This starter deck is centred around quick and efficient Xyz summons. It is based on the deck played by Yuma, the main character of the   Zexal TV se
deck_description: A 2013 TCG starter deck featuring Number C39: Utopia Ray as the cover card. Also included are 15 Power-Up cards from the Super Starter Power-Up Packs that pairs with this deck. Both Number C39: Utopia Ray V and Rank-Up-Magic Limited Barian's Force are featured cards of the Power-Up Packs. Cards in this deck are fully compatible with those you already use. You can upgrade your main deck by switching or adding cards from the Power-Up packs. Main deck: 40 cards, extra deck: 2 cards, side deck: 15 cards. "V for Victory is a starter set built around utilizing Xyz summons. This deck in particular is about quickly being able to Xyz summon Number C39: Utopia Ray. This can be seen by the number of card designs to allow players to summons Gagaga Magician and Gagaga Girl, who can quite easily Xyz summon Utopia Ray. Despite being built around one core strategy, the deck is surprisingly versatile. This is thanks to both the deck featuring a ton of monsters that can be summoned or changed in response to an opponent's action and that Utopia Ray can easily be a boost to dangerous levels of attack points." CBR.   Note: this deck was originally compiled by Spheal180 on https://cardcluster.com/deck/5DR740  Edits were only made to add the contents of the Power-Up packs.

deck_name: Swordsoul 2nd Place WCQ Greenville SC - Mike Dorn
deck_excerpt: Swordsoul 2nd Place WCQ Greenville + Discussion into Card Choices
deck_description:
Hello Everyone, this is my 2nd place Swordsoul Tenyi list that I've been playing for a few months now. I'll use this space to go over a few key choices I made for the WCQ, some tricks people may not know, and my match history.   40 Card Main Deck: One thing I was certain of this meta is that I had to be on 40 cards and it was not optional. This is because many matchups in the format are NOT WINNABLE without seeing side cards. Scythe locks, floodgates, giant boards, and cards like Zombie World are everywhere this format. Often times, drawing just engine makes the game impossible to win. I kept my deck to 40 specifically to increase my chances of drawing side cards. Both for going first and for going second. This paid off immensely today as the majority of my games I opened a blow out side card in backrow removal or something like anti-spell. Some of my ratios are a little weird because of this with things like Adhara at 2, but it was more than worth it. Droll & Lock Bird: I respect the Floowandereeze matchups a lot more than I feel other players do. If you are going second, it is almost impossible to win without seeing a side card. This is one of the reasons I main decked droll over Nibiru. This format Swordsoul plays exceedingly well into weaker boards. Often clearing the board as part of their normal combo for setup through Baxia combo lines. I am not a huge fan of Nibiru turning off your Tenyis and Droll was an excellent substitute. Every game I drew Droll, even in multiples, I won the game. Would highly recommend trying it out for those who haven't.   Heavenly Dragon Circle vs Vessel: I play 3 circle and no vessel for my spell ratios. In my own experience, I dislike vessel alot as its only great when you open it with another Tenyi. Past that its only hand advantage and doesn't contribute to the board if you have to use it after making a token. Swordsoul boards are often fairly weak and getting otk'd before you can use your resources is a major problem. I play 3 circle for a few reasons.
  1. Circle is effectively Crossout Designator. Effect Veiler and Infinite Impermanence are the 2nd and 3rd most popular handtraps behind Ash Blossom in every deck right now. Circle was a card I wanted to see in my opener every game (played 3) as it would protect my normal summon. This came up so often and completely saved me at least 5 times throughout the tournament.
  2. Second is the fact that it can turn any Tenyi into any Swordsoul. When doing your Chixiao search, you often have to decide between searching Longyuan and Blackout. With circle, you can special a Tenyi, and use it to search your starter, or a Longyuan so you can get Blackout later. This further increases the consistency of the deck as you have 14 ways of getting to your normal summon.
  3. Circle is a main deck out for Mystic Mine. In the months since the latest banlist. I looked back at my games and the majority of my losses were either to a trap floodgate, Artifact Scythe, or Mystic Mine. With circle you can tribute summon a lvl  7 Tenyi over your board and tribute it off with circle to out Mystic Mine. You can either do this on your own turn to guarantee Mystic Mine being destroyed, or you can tribute set a Tenyi over your board and set circle. During their End Phase you can tribute your monster with Circle and catch them by surprise.
  4. Many people dislike circle as many times you don't use it and they see it as a minus 1. Often times this isn't quite the case. If you have circle and go through your turn without using it, then you didn't need it. You must already be in a winning position and it didn't need to resolve in the first place. In these scenarios I set the card before passing the turn. You can combo Circle with Blackout as a cl2 to tribute your Blackout target and get your search. Furthermore, you can tribute your Wyrm on field when do a removal effect. Many times I would tribute off my own Chixiao or Monk in the End Phase to search a starter for the next turn. Then on my own turn I could use the second effect to add a Tenyi to discard for Longyuan. Furthermore, this would be a Vishuda to remove problems, or Ashuna, to get extra bodies on board for lethal.
  Forbidden Chalice vs Forbidden Droplet: I chose to run Chalice over Droplet today primarily because I was main decking Droll & Lock Bird. Many  times there is a single card on the board that is stopping your turns from going smoothly (Barrier Statue, Rexterm, Standard Boss Monsters). I found I didn't need the extra punch that Droplet provided and allowed me to keep more of my hand in the process. Furthermore, I don't play many spells in which to combo Droplets with as it was often the only spell I drew for turn. Finally, I found my biggest issue was token collector, and just having a quick 1-for-1 to deal with it instead of a 2-for-1 in Droplets was better for me. I am also siding DRNM to deal with the board breaking issue.   Geomathmech Final Sigma: I have run Final Sigma over Dragite for many months for a few reasons. The first is decks like Floowandereeze and Sky Striker. These are decks that not only need to setup, but also overcommit to beating Final Sigma. Some Floowandereeze players do not run the Extra Deck outs as there is not a single card in their main deck which beats it. This came up round 6 when I played against the Floowandereeze player who won the tournament. He used Dimension Shifter in SP and I immediately made Chixiao and used its effect to banish Blackout from deck instead of searching to make Final Sigma. It took him 4 turns to eventually waste his turn outing the card and by then I had built up enough cards in hand to easily OTKand beat him 2-0. In these matchups, Final Sigma often serves as a pseudo Mystic Mine. Against Sky Striker their only out is Accesscode Talker. If you save a monster negate, when they gain the attack, on resolution you can negate Accesscode and it loses the attack and they no longer have a way to beat it. Finally, many times on turn 3 you do a Baxia line with Taia that often banishes Blackout in the process. You have an extra token and I use Baxia and that token to make Final Sigma to OTK since it deals double damage through monsters. This comes up very often.   Important Tricks: Outing Gozen Match: There is one specific hand going first that can beat this card. Say you Special Summon Vishuda to the board and they flip Gozen Match. You can use Heavenly Dragon Circle to tribute Vishuda off and search Adhara. You can then SS Adhara and make Monk as they are both earth. From here if you have Vishuda in Graveyard or in hand you can bounce Gozen.   Outing Necroworld Banshee and Baiting with Tenyis from Hand: In my round 3 I won game 1 by doing the following line: My oponent ended their turn with a Banshee face up on the field. For those that don't know, they can banish Banshee as a quick effect to put Zombie World on the field which is a huge lock for us. In this game I SS Vishuda first and linked it off for Monk. I then normal summoned Taia and banished Vishuda. My opponent seeing that the threat was gone and that I could synchro summon used Banshee to put Zombie World in play. I then activated adhara from hand to add the banished Vishuda back to hand and use its effect in hand to bounce the Zombie world and win that game. It is very important to be aware of when you can activate Tenyis from hand when your opponent isn't expecting it. In this scenario he could have stopped my play with Huaquero but held it as I was removing my own threat. A few other times I drew Shthana and stopped my opponent from OTK'ing me by leaving a monk on field and using Shthana to disrupt their Battle Phase.   The best tip I have besides the first two is take things very slowly. Often times you can sneak a Tenyi on board or get an additional card in hand if you fully think out your plays.   Match History (going 1st/2nd) Adamancipator: 2-0 (1st) Trap Eldlich: 2-0 (2nd) Trap Eldlich: 2-0 (2nd) Swordsoul: 2-1 (2nd) Swordsoul: 2-1 (2nd) Floowandereeze: 2-0 (1st, first place finisher) Dragon-Link: 1-2 (1st) Punk Pendulum: 2-1 (1st) Punk Synchro: 2-0 (1st) I personally wouldn't change anything about the main deck as I never lost game 1 the entire day. If you have any questions or just want to talk theory feel free to reach out to me and best of luck with your own lists!
